@ENDNODE
@NODE Distribution Distribution
@TOC MAIN

    AmiCAD has been written by R.Florac. The AmiCAD package is
    Copyright ® 1998 R.Florac, it's not public domain.

    AmiCAD is distributed under the concept of giftware/emailware.
    It can be used only for personal usage, professional usage is strictly
    forbidden without my permission, contact me for that.

    It is allowed to put this program only
      Ę into AmiNet
      Ę on AmiNetCDs

    You can @{"reach me" LINK Auteur} by sending your E-mails on the net.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Requirements "Requirements"
@TOC MAIN

    AmiCAD is a program written in C (SAS C Compiler 6.58), and also with
    Devpac 3.14 for some little assembly routines.

    AmiCAD  requires the following:
      - Workbench 3.0+
      - 68020 processor or better.

    It's an electronics vector sheets editor. It uses only integers for
    faster and simpler working. It's ARexx interface gives it more than 130
    commands, user defined functions are also available. It can use it's own
    variables (integer maths and strings).
    The @{"gtlayout.library" LINK GTLAYOUT} version 39+ can be used for loading and
    looking for symbols, although it's not necessary for running the program.
    This library is not included in the package, you can get it on Aminet.

    The program can work with many windows at the same time, as long as memory
    is available. The advanced options of the 3.0 system are used: @{"AppIcon" LINK AppIcon},
    @{"Pools" LINK Pools}...
@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation Installation
@TOC MAIN

    The simplest method of installation is to use the provided Installer
    script.  The Installer program is required for this to work.
    The preference files AmiCAD.prefs and AmiCAD.keys must be copied into the
    same drawer as the AmiCAD program.
    The AmiCAD.guide @{"help" LINK "AideĀenĀligne"} file can be copied anywhere
    you like, you only have to set the AmiCAD tooltype @{"HELPFILE" LINK HELPFILE} to the
    corresponding path (HELP: for example).

    WARNING: the program can't be run without the 3.0 ROM system (or 3.1).
@ENDNODE
@NODE Running "Running the program / ToolTypes"
@TOC MAIN

    The stack used by AmiCAD can be set to 4 kB only.

    AmiCAD can be started from the CLI or the Workbench (by double
    clicking on it's icon).

    @{b}Running from a CLI (or Shell)@{ub}
    The template of the command is:

  AmiCAD FILE/M,HELPFILE/K,LIBS/K,CLIPS/K,STARTUP/K

    AmigaDOS wildcards can be used:

  AmiCAD #?.sheet   ==> all files with the extension ".sheet"
			will be loaded into individual windows.

    You can start the program without giving it a file name: the title
    "NoName" will be used by default.

    The keyword HELPFILE gives the path where the help file can be found:

  Example:
      AmiCAD HELPFILE HELP:AmiCAD.guide

    The keyword LIBS gives the path where the symbol libraries are stored:

  Example:
      AmiCAD LIBS Work:AmiCAD/Symbols

    The keyword CLIPS gives the path where the clips are stored:

  Example:
      AmiCAD CLIPS Work:AmiCAD/Clips

    The keyword STARTUP gives the program the name of an ARexx script
    that will be run at startup.

  Example:
      AmiCAD STARTUP startup.AmiCAD

    All these keywords can be associated in a single command:

  AmiCAD HELPFILE HELP:AmiCAD.guide LIBS Work:AmiCAD/Symbols NewSheet

    @{b}Running from Workbench@{ub}
    You only have to click twice on the icon of the program or on an icon
    associated to a file saved with AmiCAD.

      The program icon accepts the seven tooltypes described here:
    @{"  HELPFILE  " LINK HELPFILE},
    @{"   STARTUP  " LINK STARTUP},
    @{"    LIBS    " LINK LIBS},
    @{"   CLIPS    " LINK CLIPS},
    @{"   MASKS    " LINK MASKS}
    @{"   X_ICON   " LINK X_ICON},
    @{"   Y_ICON   " LINK Y_ICON},

      Use the Workbench Information menuitem to display and modify them.

    When the program is running, all the requesters that are open can be
    closed by clicking on the gadgets or with the keyboard, (sometimes with
    the right mouse button also). ESC can replace a click on CANCEL, ENTER
    can replace YES or OK.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "BarreĀdeĀtitre" "Title bar format"
    There are some indicators on the titlebars of the windows:
    - The name of the file associated to the document (with the @{"complete" LINK "FullĀname"}
      path or not),
    - a space, the page title,
    - some letters between two braces []:,
      - a + sign if the document has been modified
      - the letter G if @{"snap on grid" LINK "SnapĀonĀgrid"} is valid,
      - the letter R if components are placed with their @{"Reference" LINK "PlaceĀreference"},
      - the letter V if components are placed with their @{"Value" LINK "PlaceĀvalue"},
      - the letter N if components are placed with their @{"pins numbers" LINK "PlaceĀpinsĀnumbers"},
      - the letter L if lines are @{"pulled" LINK "PullĀlines"} while moving components,
      - a number that gives the width of the actual lines that are drawn (0 for
      dashed lines).
      - the cursor coordinates X=...,Y=...

    The windows have two proportional gadgets to scroll big sheets larger
    than the screen. The windows can be @{"iconified" LINK Iconify}, then they have
    no more gadgets, but they take only a little space on the screen.
    Select this window and click on the right button of the mouse to
    open it again.
@ENDNODE
@NODE HELPFILE "The HELPFILE tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives to the program the path to find the guide file.
    This word must be followed by the sign "=" and the path and name
    of the guide file. So you can place it where you want and even
    rename it.

  Example:
      HELPFILE=HELP:AmiCAD.guide
@ENDNODE
@NODE "OUTILĀWINDOW" "The WINDOW tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05.
    Document dimensions are now saved in the file AmiCAD.prefs.
@ENDNODE
@NODE STARTUP "The STARTUP tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives to the program the name of an @{"ARexx script" LINK Script}
    that will be run at startup. So you can @{"define" LINK DEF} the usual functions you often use,
    if you want.

  Examples:
      STARTUP=startup.amiCAD
      STARTUP=startup
@ENDNODE
@NODE LIBS "The LIBS tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives the path where the symbols files are found.
    The default path is the Libs sub-directory, in the AmiCAD directory.

  Examples:
      LIBS=Work:AmiCAD/Symbols
      LIBS=Symbols

  See also: @{"LIBSPATH" LINK LIBSPATH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE CLIPS "The CLIPS tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives the path where the clips are found.
    The default path is the Clips sub-directory, in the AmiCAD directory.

  Examples:
      CLIPS=Work:AmiCAD/Clips
      CLIPS=User_symbols

  See also: @{"CLIPPATH" LINK CLIPPATH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE MASKS "The MASKS tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype gives the path where the clips used by AmiPCB
    are found, to set a link between AmiCAD and AmiPCB.
    By default this path is set to /AmiPCB/Clips, so if the two
    programs directories are installed in the same place, all will be working.

    @{i}Examples :@{ui}
	MASKS=Work:AmiPCB/Clips
	MASKS=Travail:Projets/AmiPCB/Clips

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"MASKPATH" LINK MASKPATH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE _MACROS "The MACRO tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05 of the program.
@ENDNODE
@NODE X_ICON "The X_ICON tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype is used to locate the AmiCAD AppIcon on the
    Workbench screen.

  Example:
      X_ICON=10   puts the icon at the left of the screen.

  See also: @{"Y_ICON" LINK Y_ICON}
@ENDNODE
@NODE Y_ICON "The Y_ICON tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype is used to locate the AmiCAD AppIcon on the
    Workbench screen.

  Example:
      Y_ICON=500  puts the icon at the bottom of the screen.

  See also: @{"X_ICON" LINK X_ICON}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SHEET_WIDTH "The SHEET_WIDTH tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05.
    Document dimensions are now saved in the file AmiCAD.prefs.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SHEET_HEIGHT "The SHEET_HEIGHT tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05.
    Document dimensions are now saved in the file AmiCAD.prefs.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GRIDSIZE "The GRIDSIZE tooltype"
@TOC Running

    This tooltype has been removed in version 2.05.
    Grid dimensions are now saved in the file AmiCAD.prefs.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Menus "AmiCAD menus"
@TOC Main

    AmiCAD handles 7 menus, they can be used with the right mouse
    button, like any other application on Amiga. Many of them can be
    called using the keyboard, without the right Amiga key.

  @{"Project    " LINK Project}
  @{"Document   " LINK Document}
  @{"Drawing    " LINK Drawing}
  @{"Edit       " LINK Edition}
  @{"Preferences" LINK Preferences}
  @{"Scripts    " LINK Scripts}
  @{"Macros     " LINK Macros}

    Many of these menus can be called using the ARexx function @{"MENU" LINK MENU}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Project "Project menu"
@TOC Menus

    This menu has 10 entries:
    @{"Load file        " LINK "LoadĀdocument"}     Load a file in the active window.
    @{"Save file        " LINK "SaveĀdocument"}     Save the current document.
    @{"Save as          " LINK "SaveĀas"}     Sve the current document using the asl requester.
    @{"Rename           " LINK Rename}     Rename the current document.
    @{"Filenote         " LINK Filenote}     Annotate a file.
    @{"Kill file        " LINK "KillĀfile"}     Delete a file.
    @{"Other document   " LINK "OtherĀdocument"}      Open a new window.
    @{"Sheets           " LINK Sheets}              Displays the document list.
    @{"HelpĀ            " LINK Help?}     Displays the AmigaGuide help.
    @{"Quit             " LINK Quit}             Close all the documents.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "LoadĀdocument" "Project menu/Load document"
@TOC Project

    You can choose the document to load with the asl.library requester.
    This library is loaded only when needed. The window takes the name
    of the loaded file.

    If the current window is empty, the document is loaded in it.
    In other cases, a new document is opened.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-O (open) or O

    Note: you can use the @{"AppIcon" LINK AppIcon} present on the Workbench screen for
    loading a file.

  See also: @{"LOAD" LINK LOAD}, @{"OPEN" LINK OPEN}.

  ARexx call: MENU("LoadĀdocument")     Warning: solid space between
	      (ALT-SPACE) the words load and document.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SaveĀdocument" "Project menu/Save document"
@TOC Project

    The document is saved using the current file name in the window.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-S (save) or S

  See also: @{"SAVE" LINK SAVE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("SaveĀdocument")       Warning: solid space between
	      (ALT-SPACE) the words save and document.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SaveĀas" "Project menu/Save as"
@TOC Project

    The current document is saved using the asl.library requester to
    choose the filename.

    If the file already exists a requester will ask you to confirm
    that you want to overwrite it.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-A (save As) or A

  See also: @{"SAVE" LINK SAVE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("SaveĀas")     Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words save and as.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Rename "Project menu/Rename"
@TOC Project

    The asl.library requester is opened and you can choose a filename,
    the current document is renamed using this filename.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-= or =

  See also: @{"FILENAME" LINK FILENAME}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Rename")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Filenote "Project menu/Filenote"
@TOC Project

    The asl.library requester is opened, if you select a file a
    requester asks you for a note to attach to the file.

    This note will be displayed using the AmigaDOS command List or
    with the Workbench menu Icon/Information.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  ARexx call: MENU("Filenote")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "KillĀfile" "Project menu/Kill file"
@TOC Project

    The asl.library requester is opened, if you select a file, it
    will be deleted.

    Warning: you can't recover the file...

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry (dangerous...).

  ARexx call: MENU("KillĀfile")   Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words kill and file.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "OtherĀdocument" "Project menu/Other document"
@TOC Project

    A new window is opened, the asl.library requester is opened and
    you can select a file to load in it.
    If you want to open a window without loading a file, just use the
    F4 key.

  Keyboard shortcut: F3 or F4 (no asl.requester)

    The keyboard shortcuts can also be used by selecting an iconified
    window and using the key.

  See also: @{"NEW" LINK NEW}, @{"OPEN" LINK OPEN}.

  ARexx call: MENU("OtherĀdocument")    Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words Other and document
@ENDNODE
@NODE Sheets "Project menu/Sheets"
@TOC Project

    A requester is opened with all the document names. Clicking on one of
    these buttons, makes the corresponding window active.

    Another way to call a window is to do a click on the middle
    @{b}mouse button@{ub}: the requester will be opened.
    Just click on the right button to put it's window in front
    of the screen.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also: @{"REQSHEET" LINK REQSHEET}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Sheets").
@ENDNODE
@NODE Help? "Project menu/Help?"
@TOC Project

    A requester is opened to ask you the name of the node of the AmiCAD.guide
    file you want to be displayed. This file contains many items, there is
    a node for each ARexx macro, with it's name (Ex: COPY, PASTE...)
    You can also have help for each menu entry by selecting the menu entry
    with the right mouse button and pressing the HELP key.
    When there is an error displayed in a requester, if this error is relative
    to an ARexx function, just type the HELP key while the requester is open,
    the AmiCAD.guide will be opened to the corresponding node.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-? or ?

  See also: @{"HELP" LINK HELP}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Help")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Quit "Project menu/Quit"
@TOC Project

    All the documents present in memory are closed. If some of them were
    modified and not saved, a requester will ask you to continue or not.
    The program frees all memory it was using when everything is closed.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-Q or Q (all the windows are closed)

  See also: @{"CLOSE" LINK CLOSE}.

  Arexx call: MENU("Quit")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Document "Document menu"
@TOC Menus

    Documents can include several pages, they have been created in version 2.12 of AmiCAD.
    They are saved in files that have a special header, different of older files, that can
    include only one page, this older format is always used for saving pages.

    @{"New page         " LINK "NewĀpage"}     Create a new page in the document
    @{"Load page        " LINK "LoadĀpage"}     Load a new page
    @{"Save IFF         " LINK "SaveĀIFF"}     Save the current document in an IFF file.
    @{"Edit             " LINK Edit}     Open a requester to handle pages
    @{"Initialize       " LINK Initialize}     The current window is cleaned.
    @{"Iconify          " LINK Iconify}     Iconify the current window.
    @{"Hide             " LINK Hide}     Close the current window, the document is always in memory.
    @{"Close document   " LINK "CloseĀdocument"}     Close the document
    @{"Informations     " LINK Informations}        Displays some informations.
    @{"Print            " LINK "PrintĀpage"}            Printing of the current page
@ENDNODE
@NODE "NewĀpage" "Document menu/New page"
@TOC Document

    This menu entry is used to add a new page to the current document.
    A requester is used to enter the name of the page.
    A document can include 65535 pages... if they can fit in memory !
    The new page takes the dimensions of the current page being edited.
    Pages of a same document are handled by the same task, so you can't
    edit a page, while a script is working on another, unlike for different
    documents.

    Voir aussi : @{"NEWPAGE" LINK NEWPAGE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "LoadĀpage" "Document menu/Load page"
@TOC Document

    This menu is used to load a new page (from file) in a document.
    This file must have been created @{"saving a page" LINK "SaveĀpage"} or with an old version
    of AmiCAD (before 2.12).
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SaveĀIFF" "Project menu/Save IFF"
@TOC Document

    The current page is saved in a file using the IFF format.
    You can then load this file into a bitmap drawing program
    like Personal Paint, Deluxe Paint or other...
    You can also import the file with a program like ProPage or
    Wordworth.
    The files are saved using only two colours (black lines, white
    background). The grid is not represented.

    The file is selected using the asl.library requester.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also: @{"SAVEIFF" LINK SAVEIFF}.

  ARexx call: MENU("SaveĀIFF")    Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words Save and IFF.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Edit "Document menu/Edit"
@TOC Document

    This menu opens a requester allowing some operations on the pages of the document :
	- @{"Select" LINK Select}
	- @{"Save page" LINK "SaveĀpage"}
	- @{"Delete" LINK "DeleteĀpage"}
	- @{"Rename" LINK Rename}
    The window have a listview including each name of the pages in the document.
    Just select a name and press the button for the command you want to execute
    on it...

    This requester can also be opened clicking twice in an empty place of a page
    with the left button of the mouse.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Select "Pages requester/Select"
@TOC Edit

    The selected page becomes the current page, it can be edited.
    If needed it's placed in front of the screen.

    See also : @{"SETPAGE" LINK SETPAGE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SaveĀpage" "Pages requester/Sauve page"
@TOC Edit

    The selected page is saved in a file (the file is selected using
    an asl.library requester). The format of the file is the page
    format, allowing the page to be loaded in another document using
    the @{"Load page" LINK "LoadĀpage"} menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "DeleteĀpage" "Pages requester/Delete"
@TOC Edit

    The selected page is deleted, its content is forever loosed...
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Rename" "Gestion des pages/Renommer"
@TOC Edit

    A requester is opened to choose the name of the selected page.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Initialize "Document menu/Initialize"
@TOC Document

    All the objects of the current page are deleted. If the page was
    modified but not saved, a requester is opened asking you to confirm
    the operation.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  ARexx call: MENU("Initialize")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Iconify "Document menu/Iconify"
@TOC Document

    The window is closed, a small window is opened in the top of the screen,
    including only the name of the document (without the path).
    You can select this window and use the right button to reopen it.
    This menu is useful when you work with multiple pages.

    You can place the iconified window whereever you want, when the window
    is iconified again, it will return to this place.

    To close an iconified window without opening it, type CTRL-Q with the
    keyboard when it's selected.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-I (icon) I

  ARexx call: MENU("Iconify")
@ENDNODE
@NODE Hide "Document menu/Hide"
@TOC Document

    The window is closed but the document remains in memory. To reopen
    this window, click on the AppIcon, (on the Workbench screen), if it's
    the only window.
    You can also use the @{"Edit" LINK Edit} menu (Select command) if you are working
    on another page of this document. If you are working on another document, click on
    the middle button of the mouse and select the name of the document you want to
    select.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-$ or $

  ARexx call: MENU("Hide")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "CloseĀdocument" "Document menu/Close document"
@TOC Document

    This menu close all the pages of the current document. If one or
    several pages have been modified you'll be prompted to save them
    or not.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Informations "Document menu/Informations"
@TOC Document

    A requester is opened to display some information :
    copyright, number of objects in the current document, name of the
    ARexx @{"port" LINK Port}, free memory...

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-K or K

  ARexx call: MENU("Informations")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PrintĀpage" "Document menu/Print page"
@TOC Document

    The page is printed using the printer.device. The current
    system Preferences are used, (printer driver...)

    A requester will ask you for a ratio, if you reply with a value of 1,
    a pixel on screen will be equivalent to a dot on the paper, if you
    reply by 2, the document will be printed twice the size. Try to find
    the best value for your printer density and the dimensions of your
    document.

    WARNING: If the value of the ratio is 0, the operation is aborted.
    Large values consume a lot of CHIP memory.

    If you reply with a good positive value, a second requester will ask
    you if you want to print the document rotated or not, this feature lets
    you print the document horizontally, (no rotation), or vertically.

    The windows are iconified during this process to make more CHIP memory
    available. If you have any problem, try to close some windows or screens
    not in use at the moment.

    A full page button can be pressed to calculate the good ratio to make
    the page fit on the full page.

    For information, the printer driver is displayed, but you have to use
    the Preferences program of the system to change it.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-P (Print) or P

  See also: @{"PRINT" LINK PRINT}

  ARexx call: MENU("Print")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "AppIcon" "AmiCAD AppIcon"
@TOC MAIN

    When AmiCAD is @{"running" LINK Running}, an AppIcon is placed on the
    Workbench screen. It's name is AmiCAD. It's purpose is to load any
    document by dragging it's icon onto this AppIcon. Simple, no?

    This AppIcon has another function: clicking twice on it brings the AmiCAD
    screen to the front. You can use it to recover a window that was closed
    previously (see menu @{"Project/Hide" LINK Hide}).

    If the program seems locked after executing an ARexx script you can
    also try to click on it, if this situation is caused by bad usage
    of the ARexx function @{"LOCK" LINK LOCK}, the problem will be solved.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Pools" "Memory handler"
@TOC MAIN

    Pools are handled by the operating system version 3.0 and later.
    Its purpose is to have a better memory handler, it's faster and
    reduces memory fragmentation.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Drawing" "Drawing menu"
@TOC Menus
    This menu is for drawing objects on the document. All these objects
    are vector oriented. They can be modified with a double click from
    the left mouse button (a requester is opened with gadgets, depending
    on the object type).

    This menu has 28 entries:
    @{"Grid size             " LINK "GridĀsize"}
    @{"Snap on grid          " LINK "SnapĀonĀgrid"}
    @{"Choose component      " LINK "ChooseĀcomponent"}
    @{"Place component       " LINK "PlaceĀcomponent"}
    @{"Place reference       " LINK "PlaceĀreference"}
    @{"Place value           " LINK "PlaceĀvalue"}
    @{"Place pins numbers    " LINK "PlaceĀpinsĀnumbers"}
    @{"Rotation              " LINK Rotation}
    @{"Reflection            " LINK Reflection}
    @{"Alternate symbol      " LINK "AlternateĀsymbol"}
    @{"Normal position       " LINK "NormalĀposition"}
    @{"Place line            " LINK "PlaceĀwire"}
    @{"Orthogonal mode       " LINK "OrthogonalĀmode"}
    @{"Continuous drawing    " LINK "ContinuousĀdrawing"}
    @{"Double line           " LINK "DoubleĀline"}
    @{"Bus                   " LINK Bus}
    @{"Dashed line           " LINK "DashedĀline"}
    @{"Any width             " LINK "AnyĀwidth"}
    @{"Place box             " LINK "PlaceĀbox"}
    @{"Place triangle        " LINK "PlaceĀtriangle"}
    @{"Place ellipse         " LINK "PlaceĀellipse"}
    @{"  FilledĀareas        " LINK "FilledĀareas"}
    @{"Place arc             " LINK "PlaceĀarc"}
    @{"Place junction        " LINK "PlaceĀjunction"}
    @{"Place text            " LINK "PlaceĀtext"}
    @{"Place input connector " LINK "PlaceĀinputĀconnector"}
    @{"Place output connector" LINK "PlaceĀoutputĀconnector"}
    @{"Redraw all            " LINK "RedrawĀall"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "GridĀsize" "Drawing menu/Grid size"
@TOC Drawing

    With this menu, you can define the size of the grid that is
    used to space the objects on the document. The default size is 10.
    The components defined in the symbol libraries all use this size.
    But you can choose another size if you want, some users prefer working
    with a size of 5.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-Ą or Ą

  See also: @{"SETGRID" LINK SETGRID}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Grid size")   Warning: solid space between
     or MENU("Grid")        (ALT-SPACE) the words Grid and size.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SnapĀonĀgrid" "Drawing menu/Snap on grid"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the objects are placed on the grid,
    if it's not marked you can place the objects wherever you want,
    but if you place some components like that, you will have some
    difficulties when placing the wires...

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-G or G

  ARexx call: MENU("Snap")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "ChooseĀcomponent" "Drawing menu/Choose component"
@TOC Drawing

    A requester is opened to look for a component in the libraries.
    This function needs the @{"gtlayout.library" LINK GTLAYOUT}.
    The window has two lists: the left one is for the libraries,
    the right one for the symbols.

    You can load or flush any library using the buttons.
    The other buttons have the same role of the equivalent menus.

    The selected component is displayed in the upper left corner of
    the document window.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-% or %

  See also: @{"PUTPART" LINK PUTPART}, @{"LOADLIB" LINK LOADLIB}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Choose component")    Warning: "solid" space
	    (ALT-SPACE) between the words Choose and component.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀcomponent" "Drawing menu/Place component"
@TOC Drawing

    This entry enables the component mode. The current symbol is drawn
    under the cursor and you can place it on the document. If no symbol
    is valid, the @{"bgui requester" LINK ChooseĀcomponent} is opened.
    Click with the left mouse button to place a component on the document.
    You are greatly encouraged to use the option @{"Snap on grid" LINK "SnapĀonĀgrid"} to
    place the components.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-H or H

  See also: @{"PUTPART" LINK PUTPART}

  ARexx call: MENU("PlaceĀcomponent")     Warning: solid space
	    (ALT-SPACE) between the words Place and component.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀreference" "Drawing menu/Place reference"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, when components are @{"placed" LINK PlaceĀcomponent} with the
    mouse, it's reference will also be placed next to it.
    This reference can be edited by a double click on the component or
    on the reference itself. You can also move this object at another place
    with the left mouse button (click on it, and drag the mouse while the
    button is held down).
    Default references are defined in the libraries and can't be changed.

    You can call the @{"ARexx script" LINK "CallĀscript"} AddRefs to add the part numbers.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also: @{"SETREF" LINK SETREF}.

  This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀvalue" "Drawing menu/Place value"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, when components are @{"placed" LINK PlaceĀcomponent} with the
    mouse, it's default value will also be placed next it.
    This value can be edited by a double click on the component or
    on the value itself. You can also move this object at another place
    with the left mouse button (click on it, and drag the mouse while the
    button is held down). The default value is the name of the object.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    See also: @{"SETVAL" LINK SETVAL}.

    This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀpinsĀnumbers" "Drawing menu/Place pins numbers"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, when components are @{"placed" LINK PlaceĀcomponent} with the
    mouse, it's pins will be numbered, if this component is defined with
    pin numbers in the library (always in this case for IC).
    If a component is placed on the document and you want to modify
    this indication, double click on it with the left mouse button and
    click on the button "Pins numbers" to change this option, if it
    can be edited (resistances for example have no pin number).

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"SETPINS" LINK SETPINS}.

    This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Rotation" "Drawing menu/Rotation"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is selected the current symbol or the selected
    objects are rotated by 90 degrees. If you press a SHIFT key while
    selecting the menu the rotation will be anti-clockwise.
    This operation can also be performed on a clip (just select the
    menu Edit/Paste, then this one).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-R or R (clockwise)
		     AMIGA-SHIFT-R or SHIFT-R (anti-clockwise)

  See also: @{"ROTATE" LINK ROTATE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Rotation")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Reflection" "Drawing menu/Reflection"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is selected the current symbol or the selected
    objects are mirrored. This operation is done around the vertical
    axis of the objects (or horizontal if they were rotated).
    This operation can also be performed on a clip (just select the
    menu Edit/Paste, then this one).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-/ or /

  See also: @{"SYMMETRY" LINK SYMMETRY}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Reflection")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "AlternateĀsymbol" "Drawing menu/Alternate symbol"
@TOC Drawing

    Select this menu to toggle the symbol definition of a component,
    when it exists in the library. You can perform this operation on
    the current symbol being placed or the selected components.

    This feature is useful for amplifiers for inverting the +
    and - inputs. In some libraries the alternate symbol is an american
    symbol (try the resistance).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-~ or ~

  See also: @{"CONVERT" LINK CONVERT}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Alternate")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "NormalĀposition" "Drawing menu/Normal position"
@TOC Drawing

    This entry invalidates the effects of the precedents @{"rotation" LINK Rotation},
    @{"reflection" LINK Reflection} and @{"Alternate symbol" LINK "AlternateĀsymbol"}.
    You can perform this operation on the current symbol being placed
    or on the selected components.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-N ou N.

  ARexx call: MENU("NormalĀposition")     Warning: solid space between
	  (ALT-SPACE) the words Normal and position.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀwire" "Drawing menu/Place line"
@TOC Drawing

    This entry enables the wire mode (or line mode). When it's selected
    the cursor is changed (into a cross). To place a line, move the cursor
    to the start and click the left mouse button, now place the cursor
    at the end point and click again with the left button. Click on the
    right button to abort a placement.
    To stop this mode, click on the right button or select another mode.

    The current line width is indicated in the @{"title bar" LINK "BarreĀdeĀtitre"}.
    It can be modified using one of these menus: @{"Double line" LINK "DoubleĀline"}, @{"Bus" LINK Bus}, @{"Dashed line" LINK "DashedĀline"}
    or @{"Any width" LINK "AnyĀwidth"}.

    To modify a line, click on an extremity with the left button, and
    holding the button down, drag the mouse to another place.

    You can also use the keyboard to adjust a line: select the line by
    clicking on it, and use the cursor keys with the ALT or CTRL keys to
    modify the beginning or the ending of the line. You can also use the
    SHIFT key to move faster (grid size).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-SPACE or SPACE

  See also: @{"Orthogonal mode" LINK "OrthogonalĀmode"}, @{"Continuous drawing" LINK "ContinuousĀdrawing"}, @{"Double line" LINK "DoubleĀline"},
	@{"Bus" LINK Bus} et @{"Dashed line" LINK "DashedĀline"}.
	@{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}.

  ARexx call: MENU("PlaceĀwire")      Warning: solid space
	      (ALT-SPACE) between the words Place and line.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "OrthogonalĀmode" "Drawing menu/Orthogonal mode"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines are always placed horizontally
    or vertically, or at an angle of 45 degrees.
    Select this menu to toggle its state.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-| or |

  @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"SETORTHO" LINK SETORTHO}.

  ARexx call: MENU("OrthogonalĀmode")     Warning: solid space
	    (ALT-SPACE) between the words Orthogonal and mode.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "ContinuousĀdrawing" "Drawing menu/Continuous drawing"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, when @{"line mode" LINK "PlaceĀwire"} is active, a new
    line is placed at the extremity of the precedent.
    Click on the right mouse button to interrupt the continuity of
    the lines.

    Select this menu to toggle its state.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "DoubleĀline" "Drawing menu/Double line"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines are drawn with 2 pixels width.

    To stop this mode, select this entry again or choose another mode:
    @{"Bus" LINK Bus}, @{"Dashed line" LINK "DashedĀline"} or @{"Any width" LINK "AnyĀwidth"}.

    Note that the current line width is written in the @{"title bar" LINK "BarreĀdeĀtitre"}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-\ or \

  See also: @{"DRAWMODE(2)" LINK DRAWMODE}, @{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}.

  ARexx call: MENU("DoubleĀline")         Warning: solid space
	    (ALT SPACE) between the words Double and line.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Bus" "Drawing menu/Bus"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines are drawn with 7 pixels width.

    To stop this mode, select this entry again or choose another mode:
    @{"Double line" LINK "DoubleĀline"}, @{"Dashed line" LINK "DashedĀline"} or @{"Any width" LINK "AnyĀwidth"}.

    Note that the current line width is written in the @{"title bar" LINK "BarreĀdeĀtitre"}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-. or .

  See also: @{"DRAWMODE(3)" LINK DRAWMODE}, @{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Bus")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "AnyĀwidth" "Drawing menu/Any width"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines can be drawn at any width. A
    requester will ask you for the width you want. Enter a value between 1
    and 255. All the objects that will be placed after this choice,
    will be drawn with this line width.
    If you select this entry while it's marked, the line width becomes 1.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    See also: @{"DRAWMODE(-X)" LINK DRAWMODE}, @{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}.

    This menu can't be called by ARexx.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "DashedĀline" "Drawing menu/Dashed line"
@TOC Drawing

    When this entry is marked, the lines are drawn like dashed lines.
    To cancel this mode, select it again or choose another mode:
    @{"Double line" LINK "DoubleĀline"}, @{"Bus" LINK "Bus"} or @{"Any width" LINK "AnyĀwidth"}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-: or :

  See also: @{"DRAWMODE(0)" LINK DRAWMODE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("DashedĀline")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Dashed and line.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀbox" "Drawing menu/Place box"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry, the cursor changes to box mode (like
    in line mode). Click on a corner of the box you want to draw with
    the left button mouse, go to the opposite corner and click again.
    If you want to cancel the operation, click on the right button.

    The boxes are drawn using the current width.

    To modify an existing box, click in a corner, and with the left
    button mouse held down, place this corner wherever you want and
    release the button.
    To cancel the operation, click on the right mouse button.

    To modify the line width of a box, double click on the box
    and give a new value in the requester.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-B or B

  ARexx call: MENU("PlaceĀbox")       Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Place and box.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀtriangle" "Drawing menu/Place triangle"
@TOC Drawing

    Selection of this menu is used to draw a triangle, if the menu
    "Filled areas" is marked, it will be filled.

    Triangles can have any line width, as for precedent menus.

    To modify the width of an existing triangle, click twice on it
    with mouse and enter the width you want in the requester.

    @{i}Keyboard shortcut :@{ui} AMIGA-' or '

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"TRIANGLE" LINK TRIANGLE}, @{"DRAWMODE" LINK DRAWMODE}, @{"SETFILL" LINK SETFILL}.

    @{i}ARexx call:@{ui} MENU("PlaceĀtriangle")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
						between the words Place and triangle.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀellipse" "Drawing menu/Place ellipse"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry, an ellipse is drawn under the cursor.
    To place an ellipse on the document, move the mouse and when this
    ellipse is where you want it to be, click on the left button.
    You can also modify it's diameters using the cursor keys (UP and
    DOWN for the vertical axis, LEFT and RIGHT for the vertical axis). If
    you use also the SHIFT key, the modification will be faster.
    You can also use the + and - keys to modify the two axis' at the
    same time.

    To modify an ellipse that is on the document, you can use a double
    click on it or click on one of it's axis', near it's border, and
    drag the mouse. If you press the CTRL key while you are performing
    this operation the ellipse will always be drawn as a circle.

    To modify the position of an existing ellipse, click in it's center
    and drag the mouse wherever you want on the document.

    To cancel this mode, choose another placement mode (lines, components
    or connectors...) or click on the right mouse button.

    You can use the menu Rotation for a selected ellipse (Reflection makes
    no sense).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-E or E

  See also: @{"ELLIPSE" LINK ELLIPSE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("PlaceĀellipse")       Warning: solid space
	    (ALT-SPACE) between Place and ellipse.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "FilledĀareas" "Drawing menu/Filled areas"
@TOC Drawing

    When this menu is marked, rectangles, triangles and ellipses that
    are placed on the sheet are filled, either only the outlines will
    be drawn, using the current width used for lines.

    @{i}Keyboard shortcut :@{ui} AMIGA-" or "

    @{i}See also :@{ui} @{"SETFILL" LINK SETFILL}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀarc" "Drawing menu/Place arc"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry, an arc is drawn under the cursor. To place
    this arc on the document, place the cursor where you want and click on
    the left mouse button.
    To cancel this mode, use a click on the right mouse button.

    You can modify it's dimensions using the cursor keys with or without
    the ALT, CTRL and SHIFT keys. With the ALT key you can change the
    radius, with CTRL you can change the angles, the SHIFT key provides
    faster changes.

    To edit an existing arc, you can use a double click to select it and
    use the ALT, CTRL and SHIFT keys in combination with the cursor keys,
    as above. If you none of these qualifier keys is used you can move the
    arc when you use the cursor keys.

    You can also use the menus Rotation and Reflection to modify the
    selected arc.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-¦ or ¦

  See also: @{"ARC" LINK ARC}.

  ARexx call: MENU("PlaceĀarc")           Warning: solid space
	  (ALT-SPACE) between Place and arc.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀjunction" "Drawing menu/Place junction"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry a junction is drawn under the cursor.
    To place it, click on the left mouse button.

    To cancel this mode, click on the right mouse button.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-J or J

  See also: @{"JUNCTION" LINK JUNCTION}.

  ARexx call: MENU("PlaceĀjunction")      Warning: solid space
	  (ALT-SPACE) between Place and junction.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀtext" "Drawing menu/Place text"
@TOC Drawing

    A requester is opened to let you give a text to place on the
    document. If you accept this requester, the text is placed under
    cursor and you can place it where you want, just use the left mouse
    button to place it.
    To cancel this mode, use the right mouse button.

    You can rotate or reflect a text before placing it.

    To modify a text, double click on it and choose a gadget in
    the requester.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-T or T

  See also: @{"WRITE" LINK WRITE}, @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL}, @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF}, @{"LINKLAB" LINK LINKLAB}.

  ARexx call: MENU("PlaceĀtext")         Warning: solid space
	  (ALT-SPACE) between Place and text.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀinputĀconnector" "Drawing menu/Place input connector"
@TOC Drawing

    A requester is opened to ask you for the connector name. This
    object is attached to its right. The size of this object
    depends on the length of its name. Use the left mouse button
    to place it on the document.
    To cancel this mode, use the right mouse button.

    To modify an existing object of this type double click on it
    with the left mouse button, then choose a gadget in the requester.

    If you want a right pointing arrow, choose the menu @{"Drawing/Reflection" LINK Reflection}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-< or <

  See also: @{"INPUT" LINK INPUT}.

  ARexx call: MENU("PlaceĀinputĀconnector")      Warning: solid spaces
	      (ALT-SPACE) between the words.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PlaceĀoutputĀconnector" "Drawing menu/Place output connector"
@TOC Drawing

    A requester is opened to ask you for the connector name. This
    object is attached to its left. The size of this object
    depends on the length of its name. Use the left mouse button
    to place it on the document.
    To cancel this mode, use the right mouse button.

    To modify an existing object of this type double click on it
    with the left mouse button, then choose a gadget in the requester.

    If you want a left pointing arrow, choose the menu @{"Drawing/Reflection" LINK Reflection}.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-> or >

  See also: @{"OUTPUT" LINK OUTPUT}.

  ARexx call: MENU("PlaceĀoutputĀconnector")      Warning: solid spaces
	      (ALT-SPACE) between the words.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "RedrawĀall" "Drawing menu/Redraw all"
@TOC Drawing

    When you select this entry, the complete document is cleared and
    redrawn.
    It's useful after some selections, block moves, or to display the
    grid correctly after some edits...

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-Z or Z

  ARexx call: MENU("Redraw")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Clip" "AmiCAD clips"
@TOC Edition

    Clips are made of any objets, they are defined simply,
    selecting objects then using menus @{"Copy to clip" LINK "CopyĀtoĀclip"} or @{"Cut to clip" LINK "CutĀtoĀclip"}.
    They can be pasted anywhere on the sheet using the @{"Paste menu" LINK "PasteĀfromĀclip"}.
    They can also be copied on another sheet (the buffer is shared
    between the different tasks).
    They also can be saved in a file and reloaded later.

    Clips have to be done using some simple rules if you want them to be
    easily used. If you want them to be aligned on the grid, the reference
    point of the clip must be on the grid : this point is defined by the
    upper left corner of the objects included in the clip. Of course you
    have to be put the junctions on the grid.

    @{i}Voir aussi :@{ui} @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Edition" "Menu Edition"
@TOC "Menus"

    These menus are relative to the objects @{"blocks" LINK Clip} being selected.
    You can select some objects with the mouse, in two ways:
  - clicking in a zone where there is no object, and with the left
    mouse button depressed, drag the mouse. All the objects that are
    present in the rectangle you are drawing will be selected,
  - clicking on an object, this one will be selected. However if
    the menu entry @{"Edition/Multiselection" LINK Multiselection} is not marked,
    only one object at a time can be selected, except if you hold
    one of the SHIFT keys when you click.

    When a block is already selected, you can add objects using one of
    the SHIFT keys while using the left mouse button.

    To select an object that is behind another (to back), select the first
    object, then click on the second while the ALT key is pressed.

    To cancel the selection of an object or of a block, push the CTRL key
    when you use the mouse (with a SHIFT key if necessary...)

    To cancel all the selections, press the ESC key or click twice anywhere
    in the window.

    @{"Copy to clip    " LINK "CopyĀtoĀclip"}
    @{"Paste from clip " LINK "PasteĀfromĀclip"}
    @{"Cut to clip     " LINK "CutĀtoĀclip"}
    @{"Delete selection" LINK "DeleteĀselection"}
    @{"Clone           " LINK Clone}
    @{"Fix on grid     " LINK "FixĀonĀgrid"}
    @{"To Front        " LINK "ToĀFront"}
    @{"To Back         " LINK "ToĀBack"}
    @{"Double size     " LINK "DoubleĀsize"}
    @{"Divide size     " LINK "DivideĀsize"}
    @{"Scale           " LINK Scale}
    @{"New group       " LINK "NewĀgroup"}
    @{"Kill group      " LINK "KillĀgroup"}
    @{"Select net      " LINK "SelectĀnet"}
    @{"Save clip       " LINK "SaveĀclip"}
    @{"Load clip       " LINK "LoadĀclip"}
    @{"Multiselection  " LINK Multiselection}
    @{"Undo            " LINK Undo}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "CopyĀtoĀclip" "Edition menu/Copy to clip"
@TOC Edition

    This entry handles the copying of the selected objects in memory.
    If it succeeds, the selection is canceled.
    AmiCAD handles 10 buffers (clips), so you can save 10 different
    blocks (see @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-C (copy) or C

  See also: @{"COPY" LINK COPY}, @{"PASTE" LINK PASTE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Copy")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PasteĀfromĀclip" "Edition menu/Paste from clip"
@TOC Edition

    The current clip is copied under the cursor. To place it on the sheet,
    place the cursor where you want using the mouse and click on the left
    mouse button.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-V or V

  See also: @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}, @{"PASTE" LINK PASTE}, @{"COPY" LINK COPY}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Paste")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "CutĀtoĀclip" "Edition menu/Cut to clip"
@TOC Edition

    This entry deletes all the selected objects, the block is copied into
    the current clip.

    Warning: This function can modify the numbers of the objects present
	     on the document.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-X or X

  See also: @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}, @{"PASTE" LINK PASTE}, @{"COPY" LINK COPY}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Cut")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "DeleteĀselection" "Edition menu/Delete selection"
@TOC Edition

    This entry deletes all the selected objects.

    Warning: This function can modify the numbers of the objects present
	     on the document.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-Y, Y or DEL

  ARexx call: MENU("Delete")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Clone" "Edition menu/Clone"
@TOC Edition

    This entry clones the selected objects. You can obtain the same
    result using first the @{"Copy" LINK "CopyĀtoĀclip"} menu, then the @{"Paste" LINK "PasteĀfromĀclip"} menu.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-TAB or TAB

  ARexx call: MENU("Clone")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "FixĀonĀgrid" "Edition menu/Fix on grid"
@TOC Edition

    This menu fixes all the selected objects on the grid. This entry
    is useful to align some objects. The point of the objects that
    is fixed on the grid is the upper left corner.

    Groups are not correctly handled by this menu entry.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-! or !

  ARexx call: MENU("Fix")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "ToĀFront" "Edition menu/To Front"
@TOC Edition

    All the selected objects are placed before the others, so when
    you click on one of them you can reach them easily.

    Note: you can reach an object placed behind another one using
    the ALT key when clicking on them, the first time you'll get
    the first object, the second one you'll get the second object.

    Warning: This function modifies the objects numbering.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-M or M

  ARexx call: MENU("ToĀfront")    Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	  between the words To and front.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "ToĀBack" "Edition menu/To Back"
@TOC Edition

    All the selected objects are placed at the end of the list.
    So when you click on them they are not selected if there are
    other objects in the same location.

    Warning: This function modifies the objects numbering.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-D or D

  ARexx call: MENU("ToĀBack")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	  between the words To and Back.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "DoubleĀsize" "Edition Menu/Double size"
@TOC Edition

    The size of the selected elements is doubled. You can also
    use this function to double the current object under the
    cursor, or while placing an object (from a clip).

    The objects can't go outside the window to permit to the function
    to succeed.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-+ or +

  See also: @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("DoubleĀsize")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	    between the words Double and Size

@ENDNODE
@NODE "DivideĀsize" "Edition Menu/Divide size"
@TOC Edition

    The size of all the selected objects is halved. The size of these
    objects have to be a multiple of two (scale of 2, 4, 6...)
    This function can also divide the size of the currrent object placed
    under the cursor, or while placing an object (from a clip).

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-- or -

  See also: @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("DivideĀsize")     Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	   between the words Divide and size.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Scale" "Menu ╔dition/Scale"
@TOC Edition

    This menu changes the size of the selected objects giving the
    user the possibility to choose the ration of the scale operation.
    If this ration is greater than 100, the size of the block
    becomes greater, while it becomes smaller if the size is lower
    than 100.

    @{I}Keyboard shortcut :@{UI} AMIGA-# or #

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}.

    @{I}ARexx call :@{UI} MENU("Scale")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "NewĀgroup" "Edition Menu/New group"
@TOC Edition

    All the selected objects are grouped together. Then you can select
    all of them by clicking on one. The wires connected to a group can
    be used like a component, when this group is moved.
    Grouping the objects of a clip is a good way to create clips that
    look like components.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-{ or {

  ARexx call: MENU("NewĀgroup")       Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words New and group.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "KillĀgroup" "Edition Menu/Kill group"
@TOC Edition

    The selected group is deleted. All the objects that where
    in a group are unselected.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-} or }

  ARexx call: MENU("KillĀgroup")      Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Kill and group.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SelectĀnet" "Menu Edition/Select net"
@TOC Edition

    This menu is used to select a net, defined by the wires that are
    connected together. Two wires that have a commun point are on
    the same net only if they are connected with a junction.
    If the net have a label, all the objects using the same label
    will be also selected. If the net is connected to a ground, all
    the other wires that are also connected to a same type ground
    will also be selected (id. for power lines with the same reference).
    The function works for normal wires and double width lines.
    You can select either a wire or a label before calling the menu,
    but not a ground or a power line.

    @{b}Warning :@{ub} this function can modify some nets, if two lines have
    the same direction, and have a common part, without any other
    connection, this two lines will be merged using only one line.

  @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-M or M

  @{i}ARexx call:@{ui} MENU("SelectĀnet")    Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
				between the words Select and Net.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SaveĀclip" "Menu Edition/Save clip"
@TOC Edition

    This menu is used to save the selected block in a file, this
    file is selected with the asl.library requester.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-W or W

  See also: @{"SAVECLIP" LINK SAVECLIP}, @{"LOADCLIP" LINK LOADCLIP} functions.

  ARexx call: MENU("SaveĀclip")       Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Save and clip.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "LoadĀclip" "Menu Edition/Load clip"
@TOC Edition

    This menu is used to read a block that was previously saved
    in a file (selected with the asl.library requester). If the
    operation succeeds the block is displayed under the mouse
    cursor and is moved with it. Use a left mouse button click
    to place it, or on the right mouse button to cancel the
    operation.

    The anchor point of a clip is the upper left corner of the
    box defined by all the objects in this clip. If you create
    clips with this point on the grid, their placement will be
    easier later.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-L or L

  See also: @{"LOADCLIP" LINK LOADCLIP}, @{"SAVECLIP" LINK SAVECLIP} functions.

  ARexx call: MENU("LoadĀclip")       Warning: solid space (ALT-SPACE)
	      between the words Load and clip.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Multiselection" "Menu Edition/Multiselection"
@TOC Edition

    When this entry is marked, you can select all the objects
    you want, clicking on them without using a SHIFT key.

    You have to select this menu to toggle its state.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-*

  No ARexx call is possible.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Undo" "Menu Edition/Undo"
@TOC Edition

    This menu can be used to cancel the last operation that was
    done on the document in memory. But the ARexx scripts or
    ARexx functions will be canceled only if the @{"SAVEALL" LINK SAVEALL} macro
    is used in them.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-U or U

  ARexx call: MENU("Undo")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Macros" "Menu Macros"
@TOC "Menus"

    These menus are used for @{"macro-commands" LINK "EcritureĀcommandes"} and
    @{"ARexx scripts" LINK Script}.

    @{"Direct mode" LINK Direct}       Ask for a command, execute it
    @{"Call script" LINK "CallĀscript"}       Calls a selected ARexx script.
    @{"ARexx...   " LINK "ARexx..."}       20 Programmable ARexx scripts.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Direct" "Menu Macros/Mode direct"
@TOC "Macros"

    This menu allows the entry of a @{"macro-command" LINK "EcritureĀcommandes"}, then its execution.
    Note that you can also use the combination of a key ALT and a function key
    to obain 10 preprogrammed macros (see @{"Function Keys" LINK "TouchesĀfonction"}).
    It should be noted that these programmed sequences are backed up in the file
    "s:AmiCAD.keys", using the menu @{"Preferences/Keys/Save" LINK Keys}. Those are then
    reloaded during each launching of the program.

    You can cause the display of a result of a command by beginning the text
    specifying this command with the equal sign (=).

  Example:
      =4*95	 displays the result of the multiplication (4 times 95)
      =FIRSTSEL  displays the number of the first selected object

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-; ou ;

  See also: functions @{"EXEC" LINK EXEC}, @{"MACRO" LINK MACRO}, @{"MAP" LINK MAP}.

  ARexx call: MENU("ModeĀdirect")         Warning: space "solid"
				  (ALT-SPACE) between Mode and direct.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "CallĀscript" "Menu Macros/Call script"
@TOC "Macros"

    This menu allows the entry of a ARexx command, (give the name of the
    @{"script" LINK Script }, the extension "AmiCAD" is not obligatory).

  Keyboard shortcut:  AMIGA -, or ,

  See also:  function @{"CALL" LINK CALL }.

  ARexx call: MENU("AppelĀscript")       Warning: space "solid"
	  (ALT-SPACE)  between Appel and script.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "ARexx..." "Menu Macros/ARexx..."
@TOC "Macros"

    These 20 menuitems are used to define 20 commands able to be launched
    by the selection of the corresponding menu.
    At the time of the first call of the menu, the user must define
    it's command, by giving the name of the script to execute, (without the
    path).
    The calls which will follow allow the call of the defined @{"script" LINK Script}.
    The name of the script then appears in the menu.  The 20 definitions
    can be saved to the file "AmiCAD.prefs", and be reloaded automatically
    at the execution of the AmiCAD program.
    These menus can be redefined while pressing one of the SHIFT keys
    during menu selection.

    Note that the @{b}editing of a defined script@{ub} can be made in an automatic
    way in a new window by calling the menu while @{i}pressing the CTRL key,@{ui}
    (the name must naturally have been defined before).
    The program then launches the ARexx script EditScript.AmiCAD, passing to
    it the name of this script in argument.
    This script, (EditScript), must be adapted to the editor which you use
    and to your installation, it's written for my text editor, Amitex.

    The command must comprise the name of the script to be executed, (always
    without the extension "AmiCAD").
    The name can only be a maximum of 11 characters long.
    It is not possible to transmit parameters to the script.
    The communications with ARexx are made thanks to the @{"port" LINK Port} AmiCAD.0,
    (or AmiCAD.1, AmiCAD.2... AmiCAD.999 if several tasks are running at the same
    time).
    Use the command port=ADDRESS() to find the port name, if necessary.

    @{i}Short cuts keyboard:@{ui} AMIGA-0 with AMIGA-9

    @{i}See also:@{ui} function @{"CALL" LINK CALL}.

    No possible ARexx call for these menus, use function CALL.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Port" "Port ARexx"
@TOC "Macros"

    The program normally opens a port of communication with the ARexx
    interpreter during it's launching, this port is called AmiCAD.0, for
    the first task being launched. If several windows are opened, the
    second port is called AmiCAD.1, then AmiCAD.2 for the following one,
    and so (AmiCAD.999 is the limit...)
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Preferences" "Menu Preferences"
@TOC "Menus"

    This series of menus makes it possible to save certain adjustments to the
    program in the files AmiCAD.prefs and AmiCAD.keys.	These files are saved
    in the current directory.
    These files are read automatically at program execution, in order to
    reload the adjustments desired by the user.
    These two files are in ASCII format and can thus be viewed and even
    modified using a text editor.
    You can in fact, create mini-configuration files containing only part of
    the configuration, like the palette for example, (see the AmiCAD.palette
    file for an example).

  @{"Auto scroll     " LINK "AutoĀscroll"}
  @{"Backup file     " LINK "BackupĀfile"}
  @{"Save icon       " LINK "SaveĀicon"}
  @{"Pull lines      " LINK "PullĀlines"}
  @{"Display grid    " LINK "DisplayĀgrid"}
  @{"Horizontal scale" LINK "Horizontal"}
  @{"Vertical scale  " LINK "Vertical"}
  @{"Sheet size      " LINK "SheetĀsize"}
  @{"Screen mode     " LINK "ScreenĀmode"}
  @{"Palette         " LINK Palette}
  @{"Font            " LINK Font}
  @{"Configuration   " LINK Configuration}
  @{"Function keys   " LINK Keys}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "AutoĀscroll" "Menu Preferences/Auto scroll"
@TOC Preferences

    When this item is enabled, if the cursor arrives at an edge of the
    current work window, the contents is automatically scrolled if
    necessary.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    No possible ARexx call for these menus.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "BackupĀfile" "Menu Preferences/Backup file"
@TOC Preferences

    When this item is enabled, a backup file with the extension ".bis", is
    created when the sheet is saved.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also:  function @{"SAVECOPY" LINK SAVECOPY }.

    No possible ARexx call for this menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SaveĀicon" "Menu Preferences/Save icon"
@TOC Preferences

    If this item is enabled an icon is created when the sheet is saved.
    The name of the program appears in the Default Tool field.	The icon
    used is the default "Project" icon, stored in directory ENV:Sys.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    See also:  function @{"SAVEICON" LINK SAVEICON }.

    No possible ARexx call for this menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "PullĀlines" "Menu Preferences/Pull lines"
@TOC Preferences

    If this item is enabled, during the relocation of one or more
    components by using the mouse, any wires connected to these
    components will be also moved.
    When this mode is on, a L is displayed in the title bar.

    Warning:  This operation takes place only after having released
	      these components in their new position.

    Keyboard shortcut:	AMIGA-F or F

    See also : @{"SETPULL" LINK SETPULL}

    ARexx call:  MENU("Pull")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "DisplayĀgrid" "Menu Preferences/Display grid"
@TOC Preferences

    If this item is enabled, a grid is displayed on the screen.  The step
    used is that defined in the menu @{"Drawing/Grid size" LINK "GridĀsize"}.
    The screen is updated after the call of the menu.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    No possible ARexx call for this menu.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "FullĀname" "Menu Preferences/Full name"
@TOC Preferences

    If enabled, this menuitem will display the complete name of the
    document in the @{"titlebar" LINK "BarreĀdeĀtitre"}.
    If it is not, the name is displayed without the path, this allows
    more space for other indicators in the titlebar, the co-ordinates
    of the cursor in particular, when the window is not sufficiently
    wide or when the complete name is very long (multiple (sub)-
    directories)).
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Horizontal" "Menu Preferences/Horizontal scale"
@TOC Preferences

    The value associated with this menu makes it possible to define the
    default scale of the components which will be placed on the diagram.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  See also: functions @{"HSCALE" LINK HSCALE}, @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Horizontal scale")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Vertical" "Menu Preferences/Vertical scale"
@TOC Preferences

    The value associated with this menu makes it possible to define the
    default scale of the components which will be placed on the diagram.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    See also: functions @{"VSCALE" LINK VSCALE}, @{"SETSCALE" LINK "SETSCALE"}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Vertical scale")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "SheetĀsize" "Menu Preferences/Sheet size"
@TOC Preferences

    This menuitem makes it possible to define the width and the height of
    the worksheet.  The window is in fact of the SuperBitmap type, which
    makes it possible to profit from very fast operations, but requires a
    significant quantity of "CHIP" memory.

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

    See also: function @{"DIMSHEET" LINK DIMSHEET}.

  ARexx call: MENU("Dimensions")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "ScreenĀmode" "Menu Preferences/Screen mode"
@TOC Preferences

    This menuitem makes it possible to choose the type of screen used to
    display the windows.  An ASL requester is displayed to choose this mode.
    The low-resolution modes make it possible to work on certain details
    whereas the high-resolution modes make it possible to have an overall
    picture of the diagram.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-] or ]

  See also: function @{"SCREEN" LINK SCREEN}.

  ARexx call: MENU("ChooseĀmode")         Warning: space "solid"
	  (ALT-SPACE) between Choose and mode.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Palette" "Menu Preferences/Palette"
@TOC Preferences

    This menu makes it possible to choose the colours of the screen used by
    AmiCAD.  Note that these colours are saved in the configuration file.
    This function requires the reqtools.library.
    Ensure that you have a copy of it in your "LIBS:" directory.

    Warning:  Do not use a too dark a colour for colour 0, black for
    example, because then the cursor used to place wires would become
    invisible...

    There is no keyboard shortcut for this entry.

  ARexx call: MENU("Palette")
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Font" "Menu Preferences/Font"
@TOC Preferences

    This menu makes it possible to choose the font used in the AmiCAD
    screen.  In the absence of the configuration file (see below), it is
    the font chosen for the default public screen which is used.

  Keyboard shortcut: AMIGA-[ or [

  See also: function @{"SCREEN" LINK SCREEN}.

  ARexx call: MENU("ChooseĀfont")        Warning: space "solid"
	  (ALT-SPACE) between Choose and font.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Configuration" "Menu Preferences/Configuration"
@TOC Preferences

    This menu comprises three headings, making it possible to save or read
    the names of the @{"ARexx scripts" LINK Script} as well as, the various modes (run, to save
    with or without icon, copy diagram...).

    LOAD :  allows the loading of a configuration file of your choice,
    saved beforehand using the option SAVE or SAVE AS.

    SAVE : allows the saving of the preferences into the AmiCAD.prefs
    file.  This file is loaded at each program execution.
    It must be located in the current directory.

    SAVE AS : allows the saving of the preferences to a file of your
    choice (asl.library requester).

    No ARexx call for these menus.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Keys" "Menu Preferences/Keys"
@TOC Preferences

    This menu comprises three headings, making it possible to save or read
    the sequences of programmed keys (function keys, combinations of keys).

    LOAD : allows the loading of the configuration file of your choice,
    saved beforehand using the option SAVE or SAVE AS.

    SAVE : allows the saving of the preferences into the AmiCAD.keys file.
    This file is loaded at each program execution.

    SAVE AS : allows the saving of the preferences to a file of your
    choice (asl.library requester).

  See also: function @{"MAP" LINK MAP}, @{"Mode direct" LINK Direct}.

    No ARexx call for these menus.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Fichiers_Configuration "Format of the configuration files"
@TOC Preferences

    The files AmiCAD.prefs and AmiCAD.keys are ASCII format files, they
    can thus be viewed, (and also modified), using a simple text editor.
    Their format follows some elementary rules however.

    Each one of these two files starts with a heading which should not be
    changed, it in particular includes the version number of these files,
    AmiCAD recognizes only the version in force for a given AmiCAD
    version. Version 1.2 of AmiCAD uses the headings:
      "AmiCADPrefs 1.1" for the AmiCAD.prefs file,
      "AmiCADKeys 1.0"  for the AmiCAD.keys file.

    The AmiCAD.prefs file then includes several paragraphs, these
    paragraphs can be removed to create a particular configuration,
    including for example only one palette of colours (AmiCAD.palette
    file for example).

    Each one of these paragraphs begins with texts placed between two
    hooks ([Menus_ARexx], [Screen], [Palette] and [Mode]), these
    texts are followed by several lines including each different
    information.  Whole or part of these lines can be removed.

    In the same way the AmiCAD.keys file includes two paragraphs
    [FunctionKeys] and [Macros].  You can add or remove lines in each
    one of these paragraphs, to suit your configuration.

    Warning: The words located on the left of the signs = must be written
    just as they are (no major/minor changes).
@ENDNODE
@NODE "EcritureĀcommandes" "Writing a line of command(s)"
@TOC "Macros"

    The macro-commands can be carried out in local mode or by the
    intermediary of an @{"ARexx script" LINK Script}.  You can refer to the
    scripts given, for example, in the ARexx directory.  These must have the
    extension ".AmiCAD" in their name.

    Each one of these macro-commands can call one of the ARexx functions, or
    even several.  Some of them require one or more arguments, finally the
    majority of them return a result.  The program also makes it possible
    to handle @{"variables" LINK Variable }, (both numerical or character
    string type).  Also you can define your own functions.

    The call of a function is done by giving its name, followed by of one
    or more arguments, surrounded by brackets, possibly separated by commas.

    The traditional mathematical operators are of course available:

	  operator	    signs	priority

      rise with a power:      ^ 	   10
      division: 	      / 	    9
      multiplication:	      * 	    9
      modulo:		      % 	    9
      addition: 	      + 	    8
      subtraction:	      - 	    8
      AND logic:	      & 	    6
      OR exclusive	      ? 	    5
      OR logic		      | 	    4
      assignment	      = 	    2

    This last operator (=) can be used to affect @{"variables" LINK Variable }.

  Example:
      A=2, assigns value 2 to variable A.

    It should be noted that writing A=B=3 is not allowed, it will involve an error
    message "Impossible Assignment".  Rather, write A=3:B=3.

      Other operators:

      shift on the left:     <<
      shift on the right:    >>

    These two operators have a priority equal to 7.

      higher test:	      > 	 higher or equal test:	   >=
      lower test:	      < 	 lower or equal test:	   <=
      inequality test:	     <> 	 test equality: 	   ==

    The tests return the value 1 if they are true, 0 in the othercases.
    Their priority is equal to 3.

    There is a particular operator which in fact isn't one, it is the sign
    ':',  this allows the separation of two statements, (or more), in order
    to be able to place several assignments of @{"variables" LINK Variable} in the same
    function.
    Thus you can place A=2:B=3:C=0 in only one command instead of using three
    of them.  The returned result is then that of the last operation
    carried out, (0 in this example).  This possibility can also be of
    interest for the function FOR, (see further), in order to carry out
    multiple initializations at the beginning of a loop.

    It should be noted that you can place a comment in a macro comprising a
    mathematical expression by using the apostrophe seen previously.

  Example:
      DELETE(FIRSTSEL) 'Deletion of the first selected element

    Lastly, you can place several function calls on the same line, by
    separating them with a colon.

  Example:
      SETSCALE(FIRSTSEL,200,2000):SETSCALE(NEXTSEL(FIRSTSEL),200,200)
@ENDNODE
@NODE Variable "The variables"
@TOC Macros

    The variables handled by AmiCAD can be of two types: @{b}numeric@{ub }
    or @{b}character strings@{ub }.  The type is selected at the time
    of the assignment, it cannot then be changed, unless the variable
    is reinitialized, (see function @{"INIT" LINK INIT}).

    To assign a value to a variable it is enough to follow its name
    with the sign = and the value to be assigned to it.

  Examples:
      A = 1
      B2 = "text string"
      A2 = "First"+B2     gives "First text string"

    The @{"character strings" LINK "ChaŅnesĀdeĀcaractĶres"} must be framed by quotation marks
    if they are constants. Numerical @{"valeurs" LINK Nombres} are limited to integers,
    (long), use ARexx to handle real numbers.

    The names of variables can include from 1 to 21 characters, they must
    begin with a letter, the following characters are able to be letters
    (accentuated or not), numbers or the character _.

  Examples of valid names:
      TEST
      TYPE_DONN╔E
      LINE1

    Note that the program normally converts the names of functions and
    variables into capital letters during input, therefore there will not
    be a difference between two names like variable and VARIABLE, (or even
    Variable), however in an @{"ARexx script" LINK Script}, preferably use
    capital letters because the strings resulting from the interpreter are
    not converted, and inevitably the program will then differentiate
    between names written in lower case and/or upper case.

    Warning:  The variables are not usable directly with ARexx, they are
    internal to the program AmiCAD and the ARexx interpreter has it's own
    variables.	It is however possible to simply return a value of
    variable to the interpreter by giving it's name:

  Example:
      'NAME_VARIABLE'; v=result

    The contents of variable NAME_VARIABLE is thus transferred in the variable
    ARexx v.
    It is often advantageous to use internal variables with AmiCAD because
    their processing is faster, in addition it can avoid the sending of
    certain messages between the interpreter and the program, which
    involves an enormous speed profit, (see scripts Zoom and Unzoom).
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Nombres" "Numeric Variables"
@TOC Maths

    The numbers handled by AmiCAD are limited to integers.  These are signed
    32 bit long integers.
    The maximum value is 2^31-1 (2147483647) and the minimum value -2^31
    (-2147483648).
    Use the capacities of the ARexx interpreter to handle numbers in floating
    point.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "ChaŅnesĀdeĀcaractĶres" "Character string variables"
@TOC Variable

    The character strings can include an unspecified number of characters,
    (theoretically limited only by the memory size of your microcomputer),
    while starting with null strings which do not include any character.
    To define a character string, you must frame it's contents by two
    quotation marks.
    If this string includes itself one or more quotation marks, those must
    be doubled.

  Examples:
      "This is a character string"
      ""
      "It is a quotation mark "" !"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Script" "Structure of ARexx scripts"

    ARexx scripts are ASCII files, conforming to a format allowing their
    interpretation by this software.  They can include all the functions
    specific to ARexx and its libraries, (I refer you to their documentation
    for more precise details), like all the commands supported by the
    program AmiCAD, (a hundred, plus any functions defined by yourself).

    @{b}Location@{ub}
    These scripts must be located in the AmiCAD/ARexx directory.  It is
    advised to name them with the AmiCAD extension, but it is not obligatory.

    @{b}Format@{ub}
    These scripts must always start with a remark included between the
    characters /* and */, as in language C.

    The AmiCAD commands must imperatively appear in upper case.  They
    are the same ones as those which are used in @{"local mode" LINK Direct}, however
    their analysis by ARexx requires some precautions, thus these commands
    must imperatively be framed by apostrophes (') or quotation marks, in
    order to differentiate them from the internal functions within ARexx.

    @{b}Example@{ub}
    The following structure is recommended for these scripts:

/* This file gives you an example of structure possible for a
script called by AmiCAD */

options results     /* essential to recover the results of the macros */

signal on error     /* for the interception of errors */
signal on syntax

/* your program must be located in this zone */

exit

/* Processing of errors, interruption of the program */
syntax:
error = RC
'MESSAGE("Syntax error"+CHR(10)+"in line 'SIGL'"+CHR(10)+"'errortext(error)'")'
exit

error:
'MESSAGE("Error in line 'SIGL'")'
exit

    This example exists already ready in the ARexx directory, under the
    name @{b}New.AmiCAD@{ub }.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Fonctions" "List of ARexx functions"
@TOC "Macros"

  @{"ABS     " LINK ABS} computes the absolute value of a number
  @{"ARC     " LINK ARC} places an arc
  @{"ARRAYDIM" LINK ARRAYDIM} read an element of an array
  @{"ASC     " LINK ASC} returns an ASCII code
  @{"ASK     " LINK ASK} ask for a string from the user
  @{"ASKNUM  " LINK ASKNUM} ask for a number from the user
  @{"ASKTEXT " LINK ASKTEXT} ask for a string from the user
  @{"BLINK   " LINK BLINK} draws and clears an object
  @{"BOX     " LINK BOX} draws a rectangle
  @{"CADPATH " LINK CADPATH} returns the program path
  @{"CALL    " LINK CALL} calls an ARexx script
  @{"CHR     " LINK CHR} returns the character having the ASCII code specified
  @{"CLIPPATH" LINK CLIPPATH} specify the drawer containing clips
  @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT} specify the memory area used for the operations CUT, COPY, PASTE
  @{"CLOSE   " LINK CLOSE} close the window
  @{"COL     " LINK COL} number of the column where an object is located
  @{"CONVERT " LINK CONVERT} display alternate symbol for component
  @{"COORDS  " LINK COORDS} returns the co-ordinates of an object
  @{"COPY    " LINK COPY} copy one or more objects into memory
  @{"CURSMODE" LINK CURSMODE} chose an object placement mode
  @{"DATE    " LINK DATE} returns the actual date
  @{"DEF     " LINK DEF} defines a new function
  @{"DELARRAY" LINK DELARRAY} removes an array from memory
  @{"DELETE  " LINK DELETE} removal of an object
  @{"DEVPINS " LINK DEVPINS} returns the number of connexions of a component
  @{"DIMARRAY" LINK DIMARRAY} set an array
  @{"DIMSHEET" LINK DIMSHEET} dimensions the window (SuperBitmap)
  @{"DRAW    " LINK DRAW} trace a line
  @{"DRAWMODE" LINK DRAWMODE} selection of the type of layout
  @{"EDIT    " LINK EDIT} call the edit requester
  @{"ELLIPSE " LINK ELLIPSE} traces an ellipse or a circle
  @{"ENDCOL  " LINK ENDCOL} returns the abciss of an end of line
  @{"ENDLINE " LINK ENDLINE} returns the number of the line of an end of line
  @{"EXEC    " LINK EXEC} interpret a string of characters
  @{"FILENAME" LINK FILENAME} name of complete file, (including path)
  @{"FILEPART" LINK FILEPART} name of file
  @{"FINDLAB " LINK FINDLAB} look for a label
