@NODE DEF "ARexx function DEF"
@TOC Fonctions

    You can define an unspecified number of functions using the internal
    functions like any operator.  One of these functions can even call upon
    another function previously defined.  The arguments can be of an
    unspecified type, it must simply correspond to the types used by the
    functions which will be called or be compatible with the operators used.

    There cannot be more than one declaration in the same line.
    The form of these definitions is as follows:
	DEF name_function(argument...) = definition of the operations.
    Key word DEF must imperatively begin the definition, without any
    preliminary space.

    The name of the functions can include/understand from 1 to 13
    alphanumerics, including the accented letters and underlines (_).
    The first character must however always be a letter.
    The internal functions cannot be redefined.  The number of the arguments
    is limited to 15 maximum.
    This number is fixed for a given definition, (you cannot declare a
    function having a variable number of arguments).
    There must be at least one argument in the definition, but this one can
    not be used.
    The arguments must of course have distinct names.

    Examples:
	DEF EXPAND(object) = SETSCALE(OBJECT, HSCALE(OBJECT)+1,VSCALE(OBJECT)+1)
    The call of the function will be then made as for all other function:
	EXPAND(FIRSTSEL) for example.

    The redefinition of a function having already been defined is possible,
    the new definition then replaces the old one.  This can be useful when
    you try to define a complex function.

  See also :
      @{"READDEF" LINK READDEF}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ABS "ARexx function ABS"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}ABS(number)@{ub}

    This function returns the absolute value of the specified number.
    This number can be a @{"variable" LINK Variable}.

  Examples:
      ABS(-8)     returns 8
      ABS(4)      returns 4
      ABS(N)      returns the absolute value of the number in the N variable

    Note: Numbers can only be long integers.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ARC "ARexx function ARC"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}ARC(x,y,horizontal_radius,vertical_radius,angle_begin,angle_end)@{ub}

    Draws an arc. The center is specified by the two first arguments
    x and y.

    The angle_begin must be lower than the angle_end value. Their units are
    degrees (negative values allowed).

    If the operation is OK the function returns the number of the new object.

  Examples:
      ARC(100,100,25,25,0,90):ARC(100,100,25,25,90,180)   draws half a circle
      can be done with only one instruction:
      ARC(100,100,25,25,0,180)
      or
      ARC(100,100,25,25,-180,0)       (complementary)

      To draw a rounded box (x0,y0,x1,y1):  (all these lines have to be
					     placed on the same line)
      DEF ROUNDED_BOX(x0,y0,x1,y1)=
      ARC(x0+10,y0+10,10,10,-90,0):DRAW(x0+10,y0,x1-10,y0):ARC(x1-10,y0+10,10,10,0,90):
      DRAW(x1,y0+10,x1,y1-10):ARC(x1-10,y1-10,10,10,90,180):DRAW(x1-10,y1,x0+10,y1):
      ARC(x0+10,y1-10,10,10,180,270):DRAW(x0,y1-10,x0,y0+10)

  See also: menu @{"Drawing/Place arc" LINK "PlaceĀarc"}, @{"ELLIPSE" LINK ELLIPSE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ARRAYDIM "ARexx function ARRAYDIM"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}ARRAYDIM(arrayname)@{ub}

    This function returns the number of elements of an array, if it exists.
    Else 0 is returned. So you can now if an array has been declared at the
    beginning of a script.

    See also : @{"DIMARRAY" LINK DIMARRAY}, @{"DELARRAY" LINK DELARRAY}, @{"GETARRAY" LINK GETARRAY}, @{"SETARRAY" LINK SETARRAY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ASC "ARexx function ASC"
@TOC Fonctions

    @{b}ASC("text",position)@{ub}

    This function returns the ASCII code of the character in the
    text, the position of this character is given by the second
    argument, this argument must be set between 1 (first char)
    and the length of the text.

  Examples:
      ASC("element",1)        returns 101 (ASCII code of char e)
      ASC(TEXT,LEN(TEXT))     returns the code of the last char
			      in the @{"variable" LINK Variable} TEXT.

  See also: @{"CHR" LINK CHR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ASK "ARexx function ASK"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    This function has been suppressed in version 1.6
    Use one of the @{"ASKNUM" LINK ASKNUM} or @{"ASKTEXT" LINK ASKTEXT} functions instead.

    It can be defined using the following definition:
    DEF ASK(T)=ASKTEXT(T,"")
@ENDNODE
@NODE ASKNUM "ARexx function ASKNUM"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{B}ASKNUM("title",number)@{UB}          @{I}Version 1.6@{UI}

    Open a requester to get a number.
    The second argument is used for the default content of the box.
    If the user clicks on Cancel, an empty string is returned,
    in the other case, the number in the box is returned.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"ASKTEXT" LINK ASKTEXT}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ASKTEXT "ARexx function ASKTEXT"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{B}ASKTEXT("title","text")@{UB}        @{I}Version 1.6@{UI}

    Displays a requester to get a string.
    The second parameter is used for the default content of the box.
    A null string is returned if the user clicks on Cancel.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"ASKNUM" LINK ASKNUM}.

    @{i}Example:@{ui}
	ASKTEXT("Enter the first"+CHR(10)+"word then press"+CHR(10)+"the ENTER key","")
@ENDNODE
@NODE BLINK "ARexx function BLINK"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}BLINK(object_number)@{ub}

    The specified object is cleared and drawn three times.
    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE BOX "ARexx function BOX"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}BOX(x1, y1, x2, y2)@{ub}

    Place a box on the document, using the specified coordinates for each
    of the opposite corners. The width of the lines depends on the current
    line width (see @{"DRAWMODE" LINK DRAWMODE}).

    If the placement is OK, the function returns the number of the new
    object, else 0.

  See also: @{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CADPATH "Arexx function CADPATH"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}CADPATH@{ub}

    This function is used to find the program path. This can be usefull
    to find some other informations (ARexx drawer...). The returned
    string always include a trailing ':' or '/'.

    Exemple, to find ARexx scripts path :
	'CADPATH'
	cadpath=result
	'MESSAGE("ARexx scripts are in"+CHR(10)+"'cadpath'ARexx")'
@ENDNODE
@NODE CALL "ARexx function CALL"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}CALL("script name", argument1, argument2...)@{ub}

    Calls an ARexx script. The name of the script can be specified without
    any path and extension, ".AmiCAD", if the script is in the ARexx drawer
    of AmiCAD. This function can be used to call a script with some arguments
    in a @{"macro-command" LINK Direct}, (ALT-Fx), or direct mode.

    You can use 0 to 15 arguments, (@{"numbers" LINK Nombres} or @{"character strings" LINK "ChaŅnesĀdeĀcaractĶres"}).

    The execution of the script is asynchronous.
    The returned value is the script name...

  Examples:
      'CALL("EditScript","Zoom")'
      'CALL("multiply",1.5,X)'
@ENDNODE
@NODE CHR "ARexx function CHR"
@TOC Fonctions

    @{b}CHR(code)@{ub}

    Return the character having the specified ASCII code.

    Used to obtain a linefeed (CHR(10)) or a special character not present
    on the keyboard.  The code can vary from 1 to 255 maximum.

    This function can also be used to write special characters, which do
    not form part of the character set of the Amiga.  Thus the following
    characters are usable:
      - 128:  symbol of amplification (triangle pointed on the right)
      - 129:  open collecting symbol
      - 130:  symbol of OR (greater than or equal)
      - 131:  arrow directed on the right
      - 133:  symbol used for the active inputs (greater than)
      - 134:  symbol of hysteresis
      - 135:  symbol "tri-state" (high impedance)
      - 136:  symbol of an impulse
      - 137:  arrow directed on the left
      - 138:  symbol describing an analog signal
      - 139:  letter corresponding to the sign "ohm" (for the value of resistance)
      - 140:  letter "alpha" (for potentiometers)
      - 141:  letter TAU (time-constants)

    Test these codes using the macro:
      WRITE(CHR(140), 100, 100)
    You can add one of these characters (or any other to a character string
    by writing the following:
      "Arrow on the right: "+CHR(131)

  See also: @{"ASC" LINK ASC}
@ENDNODE
@NODE CLIPPATH "ARexx function CLIPPATH"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}CLIPPATH("path")@{ub}

    Determine the directory where the clips are located.  This function
    makes it possible to modify the path used for @{"CLIPS" LINK CLIPS}.

    The function returns the previous path used.  If the specified path
    is a null string, CLIPPATH(""), there is no modification of the path
    used, only the current path is returned.

  Example:
      CLIPPATH("Work:AmiCAD/Clips")
@ENDNODE
@NODE CLIPUNIT "ARexx function CLIPUNIT"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}CLIPUNIT(unit)@{ub}

    This function sets the current memory unit used for the Copy/Paste
    functions. The unit number can be from 1 to 10.
    Unit 5 is often used in ARexx scripts, if necessary.

    The value returned by this function is the number of the unit that was
    active BEFORE this call. If you want to know it without changing it,
    give a negative or null argument.

    Warning: if the returned value is null, the function couldn't get
    access to the clip. This can be possible if another task is using
    this clip in the same time (Version 2.05).

  Example of script:
      'CLIPUNIT(2)'       select a new unit (number 2)
      clip=RESULT	  keeps the old active unit in variable clip
      ...
      'CLIPUNIT('clip')'  select again the old clip unit

  See also: @{"COPY" LINK COPY}, @{"PASTE" LINK PASTE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CLOSE "ARexx function CLOSE"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}CLOSE(window)@{ub}

    This function causes the closing of the current window (argument positive
    or null) or of all the windows if argument is -1.
    There is no returned value.
    If a window was modified all the changes will be lost, use the @{"MODIF" LINK MODIF}
    function to know if saving is needed before closing the window.

    To hide a window, without losing its text in memory, use the
    MENU("Hide"), to reduce it to its minimal size, use the
    MENU("Iconify").

  See also: @{"OPEN" LINK OPEN}, @{"LOAD" LINK LOAD}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE COL "ARexx function COL"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}COL(object_number)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know the number of the column where
    the specified object is located.
    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the argument is null, the left edge of the current selection is
    returned (or -1 if there is no selection).

  See also: @{"ENDCOL" LINK ENDCOL}, @{"LINE" LINK LINE}, @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CONVERT "ARexx function CONVERT"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}CONVERT(object_number, 0/1/-1)@{ub}

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If it is null, the action will confirm the current mode of placement of
    components, (as by using the menu Drawing/@{"Place Component" LINK "PlaceĀcomponent"} for example).
    The returned value will be equal to 0 if the current mode of placement is
    the "normal" mode, if the "alternate" mode were valid the returned value
    is different from 0.

    This function makes it possible to choose the type of symbol for a
    component.	According to the value of the second argument, the action
    will be the following one:
      - equal to 0:   it is the normal symbol which will be used,
      - equal to 1:   it is the second symbol which will be used,
      - equal to -1:  symbol is changed.

    The returned value is then equal to 0 or 1 if the selected object is a
    component, if not it is -1.

  See also: menu Drawing/@{"Alternate symbol" LINK "AlternateĀsymbol"}, @{"READCONV" LINK READCONV}
@ENDNODE
@NODE COORDS "ARexx function COORDS"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}COORDS(object_number)@{ub}

    This function returns the co-ordinates of the object specified in the
    form of a character string, separated by commas.
    If the object is a line the co-ordinates are the form x0, y0, x1, y1.
    For a triangle the form is x0,y0,x1,y1,x2,y2.
    For an arc the form is x,y,horizontal_radius,vertical_radius,begin_angle,end_angle.
    For an ellipse the form is x,y,horizontal_radius,vertical.
    They are the form x,y for all other objects.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

  @{i}Example of use:@{ui}
      'COORDS('line')'; coord=result
      /* find the different coordinates */
      PARSE VAR coord x0 ',' y0 ',' x1 ',' y1

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"COL" LINK COL}, @{"LINE" LINK LINE}, @{"ENDCOL" LINK ENDCOL}, @{"ENDLINE" LINK ENDLINE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE COPY "ARexx function COPY"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}COPY(clip)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to recopy the objects selected in the
    specified memory area.  The number of the clip can vary from 1 to 10.
    Use the function @{"PASTE" LINK PASTE} to place the objects or choose
    the default unit, (@{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}), then use the menu @{"Edition/Paste from clip" LINK "PasteĀfromĀclip"}.

    The returned value is equal to 1 if all occurs normally.
@ENDNODE
@NODE CURSMODE "ARexx function CURSMODE"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{B}CURSMODE(type)@{UB}          @{I}Version 2.00@{UI}

    This function makes it possible to place the cursor in a specified mode:
    - if type is equal to @{B}0@{UB}: @{B}clip@{UB} placement mode,
    - if type is equal to @{B}1@{UB}: @{B}component@{UB} placement mode,
    - if type is equal to @{B}2@{UB}: @{B}wires@{UB} placement mode,
    - if type is equal to @{B}3@{UB}: @{B}arcs@{UB} placement mode,
    - if type is equal to @{B}4@{UB}: @{B}text@{UB} placement mode,
    - if type is equal to @{B}7@{UB}: @{B}junctions@{UB} placement mode,
    - if type is equal to @{B}10@{UB}: @{B}ellipse@{UB} placement mode,
    - if type is equal to @{B}22@{UB}: @{B}box@{UB} placement mode,
    - if type is equal to @{B}26@{UB}: @{B}triangle@{UB} placement mode.
    Any other value clears the current mode.

    The returned value is the one corresponding to the previous mode (before
    applying this function).

    To choose a text or connector placement mode, use one of the
    functions @{"WRITE" LINK WRITE}, @{"INPUT" LINK INPUT} or @{"OUTPUT" LINK OUTPUT}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DATE "ARexx function DATE"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}DATE(day)@{ub}

    Return the current date.  If the argument day is not zero, the day of
    the week is included.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      DATE(0)     returns 18-Oct-97
      DATE(1)     returns Saturday 18-Oct-97

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"TIME" LINK TIME}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DELARRAY "ARexx function DELARRAY"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}DELARRAY(arrayname)@{ub}

    This function frees the memory allocated for an array. If the
    array doesn't exists no error occurs, but a 0 is returned.
    The number of objects in the array is returned.

    See also: @{"ARRAYDIM" LINK ARRAYDIM}, @{"DIMARRAY" LINK DIMARRAY}, @{"GETARRAY" LINK GETARRAY}, @{"SETARRAY" LINK SETARRAY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE DELETE "ARexx function DELETE"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}DELETE(object_number)@{ub}

    Remove the object whose number is specified.  Return the number of
    remaining objects.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the argument is null, all the selected objects are deleted,
    if the argument is -1, ALL the objects on the document are
    deleted (Version 2.01).

    Warning:  This function can modify the numbers of the remaining
	      objects.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DEVPINS "ARexx function DEVPINS"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{B}DEVPINS(object_number)@{UB}

    This function is used to create a netlist.
    The value of the argument must be set between
    1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    The specified object must be a  component, the function
    then returns the number of connexions of this
    component, else an error message is displayed.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"PINCOL" LINK PINCOL}, @{"PINLINE" LINK PINLINE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DIMARRAY "ARexx function DIMARRAY"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}DIMARRAY(arrayname,number_of_objects)@{ub}

    This function allocates some memory to handle an array. Data
    placed in arrays can be integers or strings, the first affectation
    sets the variable type, like for variables.
    The number of objects can be set between 1 and 2^24 (16777216).

    See also: @{"ARRAYDIM" LINK ARRAYDIM}, @{"GETARRAY" LINK GETARRAY}, @{"DELARRAY" LINK DELARRAY}, @{"SETARRAY" LINK SETARRAY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE DIMSHEET "ARexx function DIMSHEET"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}DIMSHEET(width,height)@{ub}

    This function allows you to change the dimensions of the current
    worksheet. These dimensions are given in pixels.
    Use menu @{"Project/Informations" LINK Informations} to find out the
    dimensions of the worksheet.

    The limits of size available for the window depend, of
    course, on the quantity of CHIP memory installed on your system.
    Dimensions of 1100 by 700 are suitable for a system equipped with 2MB CHIP.

    Returned value:  1 if the operation succeeded, 0 if it didn't

    Warning: No control is made on the values passed in arguments.

  See also: menu @{"Preferences/Dimensions document" LINK "SheetĀsize"}, functions @{"WWIDTH" LINK WWIDTH}, @{"WHEIGHT" LINK WHEIGHT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE DRAW "ARexx function DRAW"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}DRAW(x0, y0, x1, y1)@{ub}

    Draw a line using the specified coordinates. The line width is dependent
    on the current mode (see @{"DRAWMODE" LINK DRAWMODE}).

    If the line can be drawn, the function returns the object number that
    has been placed, if there was an error 0 is returned.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"BOX" LINK BOX}, @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE DRAWMODE "ARexx function DRAWMODE"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}DRAWMODE(line_type)@{ub}

    Determines which will be the type of line which will be traced (see
    @{"DRAW" LINK DRAW}).
    If line_type is equal to 0:  they will be dotted lines,
		    equal to 1:  they will be "normal" lines (connections),
		    equal to 2:  they will be double lines,
		    equal to 3:  they will be buses.
    If type_line is lower than 0 and higher than -256, lines of a
    personalized width will be traced, with a width equal to the absolute
    value of that which was specified (v1.1).

    The Drawing menu is updated according to the selected type.

    This function returns the type of line which was in force BEFORE the
    call of the function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE EDIT "ARexx function EDIT"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}EDIT(object_number)@{ub}

    This function calls a requester making it possible to edit/modify an
    element of the diagram.  It has the same effect as a double clicking
    on an object using the left button of the mouse.
    No value is returned.

    The value of the argument must be set between 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    This function is useful when mapped to a key combination on the keyboard.
  Example:
      MAP("alt-e","EDIT(FIRSTSEL)")

    You can then select an object and use the combination of ALT-e keys on
    the keyboard to call the edit requester on the first selected element.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ELLIPSE "ARexx function ELLIPSE"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}ELLIPSE(x, y, horizontal_radius, vertical_radius)@{ub}

    Place an ellipse, the center is given by the two first args, x and y,
    the radius by the others. If the placement is OK this function returns
    the number of the new object, else 0.

    The width of the line depends on the current line width (see @{"DRAWMODE" LINK DRAWMODE}).

    To draw a circle you can use the macro:
      DEF CIRCLE(x,y,r)=ELLIPSE(x,y,r,r)

    If the x and y coordinates are -1, the dimensions of the radius are
    used to set the current radius of the ellipses placement mode.

    Use the @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS} function to get the ellipses datas.

  See also: @{"ARC" LINK ARC}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ENDCOL "ARexx function ENDCOL"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{B}ENDCOL(object_number)@{UB}

    This function returns the abciss of the point defining the end
    of a line (dashed line or any width). If the object is another
    type (component, junction or other) the returned value has no
    signification.

    The objet number must be set between 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"COL" LINK COL}, @{"LINE" LINK LINE}, @{"ENDLINE" LINK ENDLINE}, @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE ENDLINE "Fonction ARexx ENDLINE"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{B}ENDLINE(object_number)@{UB}

    This function returns the number of the line where the specified
    object (a line, any width) is ending.
    If the object is not a line the returned value is no significant.

    The objet number must be set between 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"COL" LINK COL}, @{"LINE" LINK LINE}, @{"ENDCOL" LINK ENDCOL}, @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE EXEC "ARexx function EXEC"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}EXEC("character string")@{ub}

    Request the interpretation and execution of the character string passed
    in the argument, as if it were about a line of command.
    The result depends naturally on the contents of the string passed in
    the argument.

  Example:
      EXEC(READTEXT(OBJECT))  interprets the line of text associated with the
			      object specified
      EXEC(READMAP("CTRL-)")  carries out the sequence associated with the
			      combination with keys CTRL -)
      EXEC(READMAP("F5"))     executes the associated sequence for key F5.

    Using a function in the @{"startup" LINK STARTUP} file can be usefull:
	DEF EXECKEY(X)=EXEC(READMAP(X))
	you can there write :
	    EXECKEY("F5")
	    or
	    EXECKEY("CTRL-)")
@ENDNODE
@NODE FILENAME "ARexx function FILENAME"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}FILENAME(name)@{ub}

    The current document is renamed with the file name given in the argument.
    If it's an empty string ("") no renaming is performed, it only returns
    the current name of the document, with complete path.

  See also: @{"FILEPART" LINK FILEPART}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FILEPART "ARexx function FILEPART"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}FILEPART("name")@{ub}

    Renames the current document, preserving the path.
    If a null string ("") is passed in the argument, this function returns
    the name of the current document, without the complete path.

  Example:
      Let us suppose that the file running is "RAM:sources/Scheme" function
      FILEPART("") would return Scheme, whereas the function
      FILEPART("New scheme") would rename the file to
      "RAM:sources/New scheme".

  See also: @{"FILENAME" LINK FILENAME}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FINDLAB "ARexx function FINDLAB"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{b}FINDLAB(first_object,"Label")@{ub}

    This function searchs for a wire with the specified label.
    The first argument defines where the search begins. It must be set
    between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the object number is negative, the search will be done only on
    the selected objects (Version 2.09).

    The returned value is the object number that was found (if any)
    or 0.

    The search is no case sensitive. You can include some AmigaDOS
    jokers (#?) in the label string.

    @{i}Note:@{ui} it's the number of the wire object that is returned,
    not the label one (use @{"GETLABEL" LINK GETLABEL} to have this one).

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
	FINDLAB(1,"0")  Return the number of the first wire with label 0
	FINDLAB(1,"Lab#?")  Retun the number of the first label beginning
			with letters 'Lab'
@ENDNODE
@NODE FINDLINE "ARexx function FINDLINE"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{B}FINDLINE(first_object,x,y)@{UB}         @{I}Version 1.4@{UI}

    This function searchs for a line at the specified coordinates. It
    is used to build netlists.
    The first argument defines where the search begins. It must be set
    between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the object number is negative, the search will be done only on
    the selected objects (Version 2.09).

    The returned value is the object number that was found (if any)
    or 0. If the founded line is beginning or ending exactly at the
    specified coordinates, the result is in negative form.

    Warning: vertical or horizontal lines only are checked.
    Other lines are only checked on their extremities.
    Only lines with a width of 1 are checked (wires).
    To draw frames or anything else than a circuitry, use
    the @{"special lines" LINK AnyĀwidth}".

    @{I}Example :@{UI}
    to know if a line is present on coordinates x0,y0
    'ABS(FINDLINE(1,'x0','y0'))'; l=result
    if l>0 then line_is_present

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"FINDOBJ" LINK FINDOBJ}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FINDOBJ "ARexx function FINDOBJ"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}FINDOBJ(first_object,type,x,y)@{ub}          @{I}Version 1.4@{UI}

    This function searchs for an object at the specified coordinates.

    The first argument defines where the search begins. It must be set
    between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If this value is set to 1, all the objects on the current document
    will be scanned.
    If the object number is negative, the search will be done only on
    the selected objects (Version 2.09).

    The second argument gives the type of object that is searched (as
    returned by the @{b}TYPE@{ub} function). If it is 0, the first object
    found will be returned.

    The coordinates must match an extremity for lines, or the point
    where the cursor was at the moment the object was placed. For the
    components it is the point where the cursor was when it was placed
    (upper left corner). If one of the coordinates is negative, it
    is not taken in account, if the two are negatives, the object
    will be found elsewhere it is placed.

    The returned value is the object number of the object that was found,
    else 0.

    @{I}Examples :@{UI}
    FINDOBJ(1,1,-1,-1)  returns the number of the first component.
    FINDOBJ(1,2,100,200) returns the number of a line that have an
	extremity at 100,200, if there is on there.
    FINDOBJ(1,7,50,-1)  returns the number of the first junction
	placed on column 50.
    FINDOBJ(-100,1,-1,-1) returns the number of the first selected
    component (if any) with an object number greater than 100.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"FINDLINE" LINK FINDLINE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FINDPART "ARexx function FINDPART"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}FINDPART(first_object,"component")@{ub}

    Begin the search for the component whose name is specified on the
    current document.
    This name corresponds in the name of the symbol, "RESISTANCE" for
    example for a resistance.
    The first argument is used to begin search after an object already
    found.  This argument must take a value ranging between 1 (search
    will be carried out on all the objects of the diagram) and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the object number is negative, the search will be done only on
    the selected objects (Version 2.09).

    Search is carried out without taking into account the case of letters,
    i.e. upper case and lower case are not differentiated.  In addition,
    you can include "wildcards" (or general characters) in the required
    string, (see AmigaDOS documentation for the various possibilities).

    The returned value is equal to the number of the object which was
    found, or to 0 if no object corresponds.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      'FINDPART(1,"RESISTANCE")'; object=result
      'FINDPART(1,"(Res|Cond)#?")'
@ENDNODE
@NODE FINDREF "ARexx function FINDREF"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}FINDREF(first_object, "reference")@{ub}

    Begin the search for the component whose reference is specified, R3 for
    example for a resistance or IC9 for an integrated circuit.
    The first argument is used to begin the search after an object already
    found.  This argument must take a value ranging between 1 (search will be
    carried out on all the objects of the diagram) and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the object number is negative, the search will be done only on
    the selected objects (Version 2.09).

    Search is carried out without taking into account the case of letters,
    i.e. upper case and lower case are not differentiated.  In addition,
    you can include "wildcards" (or general characters) in the required
    string, (see AmigaDOS documentation for the various possibilities).

    The returned value is equal to the number of the object which was
    found, or to 0 if no object corresponds.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      'FINDREF(1,"R4")'; object=result
      'FINDREF(1,"R#?")'; object=result
      IF(O=FINDREF(1,"C2"),BLINK(O),0)

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"FINDVAL" LINK FINDVAL}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FINDVAL "ARexx function FINDVAL"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}FINDVAL(first_object, "value")@{ub}

    Begin the search for the component whose value or type is specified, 10k
    for example for a resistance or 7400 for an integrated circuit.
    The first argument is used to begin search after an object already
    found.  This argument must take a value ranging between 1 (search will be
    carried out on all the objects of the diagram) and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the object number is negative, the search will be done only on
    the selected objects (Version 2.09).

    Search is carried out without taking into account the case of letters,
    i.e. upper case and lower case are not differentiated.  In addition,
    you can include "wildcards" (or general characters) in the required
    string, (see AmigaDOS documentation for the various possibilities).

    The returned value is equal to the number of the object which was
    found, or to 0 if no object corresponds.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      'FINDVAL(1,"10k")'; object=result
      IF(O=FINDVAL(1,"10ĄF"),MARK(O),0)

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"FINDREF" LINK FINDREF}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FIRSTSEL "ARexx function FIRSTSEL"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}FIRSTSEL@{ub}

    This function returns the number of the first selected object.  It does
    not require any argument.  If no object is marked the returned value is
    null.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"NEXTSEL" LINK NEXTSEL}
@ENDNODE
@NODE FONTNAME "ARexx function FONTNAME"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}FONTNAME@{ub}			 Version 2.05 (argument suppressed)

    Return the name of the font used in the current window.

  @{i}Example:@{ui}
      FONTNAME	    returns topaz.font (for example)

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"FONTSIZE" LINK FONTSIZE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FONTSIZE "ARexx function FONTSIZE"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}FONTSIZE@{ub}			 Version 2.05 (argument suppressed)

    Return the size of the font used in the current window.

  @{i}Example:@{ui}
      FONTSIZE	    returns 11 (for example)

  See also: @{"FONTNAME" LINK FONTNAME}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FOR "ARexx function FOR"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}FOR(init,condition_end,action1,...)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to define loops.  The first argument
    (init) is carried out only once, when the call of the function has been
    just made.	The second argument defines the condition to end the loop.
    Finally the third argument as well as the following arguments if they
    exist are evaluated with each execution of the loop.

    The use of this function often allows a saving of significant time in
    the execution of a script, the number of messages can decrease to a
    significant degree if it is used advisedly.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      FOR (I=0, I<10, I=I+1)
      In this example @{"variable" LINK Variable} I is initialized with value
      0, as long as this value is lower than 10, one increments this value.
      I, thus will successively take values 1 to 10.

      FOR (I=1, I<=10, I=I+1, DELETE(I))
      This formula includes an additional instruction making it possible to
      remove the first 10 objects.

      N=100:FOR (I=0:J=0, I<=N, J=J+I, I=I+1):J
      This formula makes it possible to calculate the sum of the first 100
      numbers.	The result of the sum is returned (:J at the end).

    Note:  A blocked loop can be stopped by two means:	either by the
    maximum number of loops (defined by function @{"SECURITY" LINK SECURITY},
    or while pressing simultaneously on three keys CTRL, ALT and ESC.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"WHILE" LINK WHILE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETARRAY "ARexx function GETARRAY"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}GETARRAY(arrayname,ord)@{ub}

    This function returns the value of a variable in an
    array. Ord must be included between 0 and the size
    of the array minus 1.

    See also: @{"ARRAYDIM" LINK ARRAYDIM}, @{"DIMARRAY" LINK DIMARRAY}, @{"DELARRAY" LINK DELARRAY}, @{"SETARRAY" LINK SETARRAY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETCOLOR "ARexx function GETCOLOR"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}GETCOLOR(colour)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to find the RGB levels of a given colour.
    The number of the colour can vary from 0 to 15.  The levels are returned
    in the form $rrr, $ggg, $bbb in a character string.  This string is the
    same form as that which is in the preference file.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SETCOLOR" LINK SETCOLOR}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETDEVS "ARexx function GETDEVS"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}GETDEVS("circuit_name")@{ub}         Version 1.4

    This function returns the number of gates in a circuit present in a
    library of symbols. The name can be specified in lower or uppercase.

    If the component doesn't exist or is not in the libraries that are loaded
    in memory, the message "Incorrect argument name" is displayed.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      GETDEVS("LM324")    returns 4 (4 amplifiers)
      GETDEVS("4011")     returns 4 (4 NAND gates)
      GETDEVS("4017")     returns 1 (1 counter)
      GETDEVS("RESISTANCE") returns 0 (no pins number)

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"READDEV" LINK READDEV}, @{"SETDEV" LINK SETDEV}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETLABEL "ARexx function GETLABEL"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{b}GETLABEL(object_number)@{ub}

    Return the number of the label object associated to the specified
    object (a line).
    The object number must be the number of a line object.
    If this object is another type, -1 is returned.
    If the label doesn't exist, 0 is returned.

    The object number must be included between 1 and
    @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    @{I}Example :@{UI} READTEXT(GETLABEL(FIRSTSEL))

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"SETLABEL" LINK SETLABEL}, @{"FINDLAB" LINK FINDLAB}, @{"LINKLAB" LINK LINKLAB}, @{"UNLINK" LINK UNLINK}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETLINE "ARexx function GETLINE"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{B}GETLINE("title1","title2")@{UB}

    This function permits to define a line with the mouse. The first
    title is displayed in the title bar while waiting for the first
    click on the left mouse button by the user. After it's done, the
    second title is displayed and a line is drawn when the mouse is
    moved. At the second click the coordinates are returned (the
    format is the same than with the @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS} function). The function
    can be cancelled at any time if the user uses the keyboard or
    another mouse button (a null string is returned in this case).

    The current preferences are used to draw the line (orthogonal,
    fix on grid...)

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"SETORTHO" LINK SETORTHO}, @{"SNAPGRID" LINK SNAPGRID}, @{"GETZONE" LINK GETZONE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETMASK "ARexx function GETMASK"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    This function returns the string defining the PCB mask
    associated to a component, if it exists (returns "" else).
    Naturely, the object number must correspond to a component
    or an error will occur (Incorrect object type).

    See also : @{"SETMASK" LINK SETMASK}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETNET "ARexx function GETNET"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{b}GETNET(object_number)@{ub}

    This function returns the number of the line object linked
    to a label. The object number must be the one of a label,
    or a value of -1 is returned.

    See also : @{"GETLABEL" LINK GETLABEL}, @{"SETLABEL" LINK SETLABEL}, @{"LINKLAB" LINK LINKLAB}, @{"FINDLAB" LINK FINDLAB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETPART "ARexx function GETPART"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}GETPART("name_component")@{ub}

    This function has been removed in version 2.0. Use function
    @{"PUTPART" LINK PUTPART} in place.

    You can use the next definition to replace it, in the
    startup.AmiCAD file, by example, see tooltype @{"STARTUP" LINK STARTUP}):
    DEF GETPART(C)=PUTPART(C,-1,-1)
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETPOINT "ARexx function GETPOINT"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{B}GETPOINT("title")@{UB}       @{I}Version 1.6@{UI}

    This function displays the specified message in the title bar
    and returns the coordinates of the point where the user clicks
    with the left mouse button.
    These coordinates are returned under the form column*32768+line.
    To get the coordinates, you can use something like that in an
    ARexx script:
    'GETPOINT("Click on a point")'
    p=result
    col=bitand(p,'FFFF0000'x)
    col=col/32768
    line=bitand(p,'FFFF'x)

    If the user clicks on the right mouse button or on the keyboard
    the returned value is -1 (operation cancelled).

    The next macros can be defined to recover the coordinates of the
    point :
    DEF POINTLINE(P)=P&0xFFFF
    DEF COLONN(P)=P>>15
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETPOS "ARexx function GETPOS"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{B}GETPOS(object_number)@{UB}

    Returns a value defining the placement mode of a component,
    a text or a connector. If the object was placed without any
    rotation, this value is equal to 1, else it can be 2 to 4.
    If the specified object had a symmetry, the returned value
    is negative.

    If the object is another type the returned value is always 0.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"ROTATE" LINK ROTATE}, @{"SYMMETRY" LINK SYMMETRY}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETREF "ARexx function GETREF"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}GETREF(object_number)@{ub}

    Returns the reference's object number that's associated with the
    specified component.
    The number of the object passed in the argument must naturally be a
    component.
    If the object is of another type the function returns -1.
    If this reference does not exist the function returns 0.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

  Example : READTEXT(GETREF(FIRSTSEL))

  See also: @{"SETREF" LINK SETREF}, @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF}, @{"UNLINK" LINK UNLINK}, @{"GETVAL" LINK GETVAL}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETVAL "ARexx function GETVAL"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}GETVAL(object_number)@{ub}

    Returns the value's object number that's associated with the specified
    component.
    The number of the object passed in argument must naturally be a
    component.
    If the object is of another type the function returns -1.
    If this reference does not exist the function returns 0.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

  @{i}Example :@{ui} READTEXT(GETVAL(FIRSTSEL))

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SETVAL" LINK SETVAL}, @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL}, @{"UNLINK" LINK UNLINK}, @{"GETREF" LINK GETREF}
@ENDNODE
@NODE GETZONE "ARexx function GETZONE"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{B}GETZONE("title")@{UB}           Version 2.05 (Second argument removed)

    This fonction permits to define a box using the mouse. The title
    is displayed in the title bar during the operation.
    To define the zone, the user must click on the left mouse button,
    keeps it while movin the mouse, and leaves it when the mouse is at
    the second corner.
    Any action on the keyboard or on another button cancel the
    function (a null string is then returned).
    If the function succeeds, a string defining the coordinates is
    returned (like by the @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS} function.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"GETLINE" LINK GETLINE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GROUP "ARexx function GROUP"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}GROUP(object_number1,object_number2...)@{ub}

    Create a new group with all the specified objects.
    Returns the number of the new group.

    GROUP(object_number)            Only one argument
    Returns the group number of the object (0 if not included in a group).

    The object numbers must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

  See also: @{"UNGROUP" LINK UNGROUP}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE HEIGHT "ARexx function HEIGHT"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}HEIGHT (object_number)@{ub}

    Returns the height of the specified object, in pixels.
    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If it's null, the height of the selected block is returned (-1
    if nothing is selected).

  See also: @{"WIDTH" LINK WIDTH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE HELP "ARexx function HELP"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}HELP("node")@{ub}

    This function allows the call of AmigaGuide, as by the menu
    @{"Project/Help" LINK "Help?"}. The argument must be the name of a node, (node),
    of the AmiCAD.guide file. You can specify the name of any function or
    menu.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      HELP("CopyĀtoĀclip")
      HELP("DRAW")
@ENDNODE
@NODE HSCALE "ARexx function HSCALE"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}HSCALE(object_number)@{ub}

    This function returns the value of the horizontal scale of the specified
    object.
    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the argument is null, the current horizontal scale is returned (v2.07).

  See also: @{"VSCALE" LINK VSCALE}, @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE IF "ARexx function IF"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}IF(x, a1, a2)@{ub}

    If x is different from zero, returns a1 if not returns a2.	Only a1 OR a2
    will be evaluated, according to the result of x.
    Note that the arguments a1 and a2 can be of any type, they can also call
    upon other functions, including other IF functions.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      IF(A>B,A,B)                 returns the maximum value of A and B
      DEF MIN(A,B)=IF(A<B,A,B)    definition function MIN
      IF(GETPART(ASK("Component?")),MENU("PlacerĀcomposant"),0)
@ENDNODE
@NODE INIT "ARexx function INIT"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}INIT(variable,...)@{ub}

    This function is identical to function @{"RESET" LINK RESET}, however the type is
    re-initialized, i.e. that @{"variable" LINK Variable} will be able to then take any
    authorized type, (numerical or character string).
    The number of arguments is unspecified.

    @{I}Example :@{UI}
    A=1        Variable A is numeric type
    ...
    INIT(A)         A is initialized (the type is loosed)
    ...
    A="String chars"    Variable A is now a string

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"RESET" LINK RESET}
@ENDNODE
@NODE INPUT "ARexx function INPUT"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}INPUT("name", x, y)@{ub}

    Place a connector with the specified name, at the co-ordinates x, y.
    The arrow of the connector is directed towards the left.
    If the function succeeds, it returns the number of the object, if not 0.

    The current vertical scale and the horizontal scale are taken into
    account to determine the dimensions of this element, (see @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE},
    @{"ROTATE" LINK ROTATE}, @{"SYMMETRY" LINK SYMMETRY}).

  See also: @{"OUTPUT" LINK OUTPUT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE JUNCTION "ARexx function JUNCTION"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}JUNCTION(x,y)@{ub}

    Place a junction at the specified coordinates. The current vertical
    and horizontal scales are used to draw it, (see @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}).

    If the placement is OK, this function returns the number of the new
    object, else 0.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LANGUAGE "ARexx function LANGUAGE"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}LANGUAGE@{ub}	    Version 2.07

    Retuns the name of the "locale" used by the system.
    For the french the string "franńais.language" is returned.
    This function permits to localize the ARexx scripts.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LEN "ARexx function LEN"
@TOC "TraitementĀchaŅnes"

    @{b}LEN("string")@{ub}

    Return the length of the character string passed in the argument.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LIBRARY "ARexx function LIBRARY"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets
@{B}LIBRARY (object_number)@{UB}

    The name of the library where is located the specified component
    is returned, if any, in another case, a null string is returned.
    The name is complete (with path).

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    @{I}Voir aussi :@{UI} @{"PARTNAME" LINK PARTNAME}, @{"PUTPART" LINK PUTPART}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LIBSPATH "ARexx function LIBSPATH"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}LIBSPATH("path")@{ub}

    Defines the path where the symbols files are found. This function can
    modify the path specified by the @{"LIBS" LINK LIBS} tooltype at any moment.

    The function returns the path that was in use BEFORE it was called.
    If the specified path is the null string, the current path is not modified:
    LIBSPATH(""). Use it to find the location of the libraries.

    @{i}Example:@{ui}
      'LIBSPATH("Work:AmiCAD/Symbols")'; oldpath=result
      ....
      'LIBSPATH("'oldpath'")'           /* set the initial path */
@ENDNODE
@NODE LINE "ARexx function LINE"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}LINE(object_number)@{ub}

    This function returns the number of the line where the specified object
    is located.
    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the argument is null, the top edge of the current selection is
    returned (or -1 if there is no selection).

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"COL" LINK COL}, @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LINKLAB "ARexx function LINKLAB"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{b}LINKLAB(object1,object2)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to link a label to a line. An
    object must be a text, and it must not be connected to another
    wire or another component (value, reference). The other argument
    must be a line number.

    The arguments must be included between 1 et @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}, they
    can be placed in any order.

    @{I}Example :@{UI} LINKLAB(FIRSTSEL,NEXTSEL(FIRSTSEL))

    @{I}See also:@{UI} @{"FINDLAB" LINK FINDLAB}, @{"GETLABEL" LINK GETLABEL}, @{"SETLABEL" LINK SETLABEL}, @{"UNLINK" LINK UNLINK}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LINKREF "ARexx function LINKREF"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}LINKREF(object1,object2)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to assign an reference to a component.
    The reference object must be of the text type and does not have to be
    already related to another component.

    The object numbers must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS},
    they can be placed in any order.

  @{i}Example :@{ui}
    LINKREF(FIRSTSEL,NEXTSEL(FIRSTSEL))

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SETREF" LINK SETREF}, @{"GETREF" LINK GETREF}, @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL}, @{"SETVAL" LINK SETVAL}, @{"GETVAL" LINK GETVAL}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LINKVAL "ARexx function LINKVAL"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}LINKVAL(object1,object2)@{ub}

    This function links two objects, one must be a component and
    the other a text. The component must be without a value before
    this operation, the text is associated to it as its value.

    The object numbers must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS},
    they can be placed in any order.

  @{i}Example :@{ui}
    LINKVAL(FIRSTSEL,NEXTSEL(FIRSTSEL))

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SETREF" LINK SETREF}, @{"GETREF" LINK GETREF}, @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF}, @{"SETVAL" LINK SETVAL}, @{"GETVAL" LINK GETVAL}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOAD "ARexx function LOAD"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}LOAD("name_file")@{ub}

    Load the file diagram specified into the current window.  The window
    loses its contents, even if it had been modified.  Use command @{"MODIF" LINK MODIF}
    to know if the diagram was modified since the last save.  The window
    takes the name of the file which was loaded.
    Return 0 if it succeeded, if not an error code.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"OPEN" LINK OPEN}, @{"SAVE" LINK SAVE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOADCLIP "ARexx function LOADCLIP"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}LOADCLIP(unit_clip,"file")@{ub}

    Load the file specified into the specified unit.  If the file name
    doesn't include any path, the search is carried out in the current path,
    then in the path specified by the tooltype @{"CLIPS" LINK CLIPS}.

    Warning:  The clip is not placed under the cursor or on the diagram,
    use the menu @{"Edition/Paste from clip" LINK "PasteĀfromĀclip"} or the function @{"PASTE" LINK PASTE}
    for that.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}, @{"SAVECLIP" LINK SAVECLIP}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOADKEYS "ARexx function LOADKEYS"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}LOADKEYS("macro_file")@{ub}

    This function has been suppressed inversion 2.05
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOADLIB "ARexx function LOADLIB"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}LOADLIB("name_library")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to load a library of symbols into
    memory, it returns 0 if the library was loaded.
    If the name of the library does not include a directory or "device"
    (DF0:, Work:, etc...), a search will be carried out in the current path
    then in the path specified by the tooltype @{"LIBS" LINK LIBS}.

  @{i}Example :@{ui} LOADLIB("Symbols CMOS")

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"REMLIB" LINK REMLIB}, @{"LIBSPATH" LINK LIBSPATH}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOADPREF "ARexx function LOADPREF"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}LOADPREF("nom_fichier")@{ub}

    This function has been suppressed inversion 2.05
@ENDNODE
@NODE LOCK "ARexx function LOCK"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{b}LOCK@{ub}	    Version 2.05 (argument removed)

    Lock the current window. All during the execution of
    the script the user cannot have access to the document any more:  the
    menus are not accessible and any operations made using the keyboard or
    the mouse are not taken into account.
    If a locking is carried out on an already blocked window, a counter is
    incremented, it is necessary then that the window is freed as many times
    as it was blocked before it is actually unlocked.

    Returned value: code equal to or higher than zero if successful operation,
    -1 if impossible to lock, (lack of memory?).

    Foot-note: The windows are automatically freed when the execution of a
    script finishes.  If there is a blocking you can also put an end to
    this situation by clicking twice on the program's AppIcon located on the
    Workbench screen.  This function cannot be called via macro since there
    would be risk of totally blocking the keyboard input/output.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"UNLOCK" LINK UNLOCK}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MACRO "ARexx function MACRO"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}MACRO(x)@{ub}

    This function has been removed in version 2.04. It can be replaced
    using something like @{"EXEC(READMAP(key))" LINK EXEC}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MAP "ARexx function MAP"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}MAP("combination keys", "sequence")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to program a macro-command, which will be
    executed when a specific key combination is used.
    Keys ALT, SHIFT and CTRL can be used as qualifiers, (it is necessary to
    use at least one of them, except for function keys).
    Only single character keys are definable (for the moment): you cannot
    define, using this function, either some special keys or the arrows.

    The sequence can include any other command, it must be included  between
    brackets, (character string).  The definition can start with the sign =,
    the result of the macro is then automatically displayed, if there is one.

    Note that these definitions are saved in the AmiCAD.keys configuration
    file when the @{"Preferences" LINK Configuration} are saved, and are thus reloaded at the
    execution of the program.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      MAP("shift-ctrl-a","SAVE(""Prog:Projects/Schemes/New scheme"")")
      MAP("CTRL-)","CALL(""Swap"")")
      MAP("F10","WTOBACK")

  @{i}See also:@{ui}
      @{"READMAP" LINK READMAP}, @{"UNMAP" LINK UNMAP}, definition of @{"Function keys" LINK "TouchesĀfonction"}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MARK "ARexx function MARK"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}MARK(object_number,...)@{ub}

    Allows the selection of one or more objects.
    The object numbers must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS }.

    If argument value is -1, then all unselected components on the
    sheet are marked.

    This function returns the number of objects which were actually selected,
    (the objects which were @{b}already@{ub} selected are @{b}not@{ub} counted).

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"UNMARK" LINK UNMARK}, @{"MARKZONE" LINK MARKZONE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MARKZONE "ARexx function MARKZONE"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}MARKZONE(x0, x1, y0, y1)@{ub}

    Allows the selection of objects included in the rectangle defined by the
    co-ordinates x0, y0 and x1, y1.  The elements must be entirely in the
    zone to be selected.
    This function does not return any particular value.

    To select the whole diagram, use the following command:
      MARKZONE(0,0,WWIDTH(-1)-1,WHEIGHT(-1)-1)

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"MARK" LINK MARK}, @{"UNMARK" LINK UNMARK}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MASKPATH "ARexx function MASKPATH"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"


    @{B}MASKPATH("path")@{UB}

    Defines the path where the clips used by AmiPCB can be found.
    This function can modify the path defined by the @{"MASKS" LINK MASKS} tooltype.

    This function returns the path used before it was called.
    If the specified path is an empty string, the path is not
    modified: MASKPATH(""), then the current path is returned.

    @{I}Example :@{UI}
	MASKPATH("Work:AmiPCB/Clips")
@ENDNODE
@NODE MENU "ARexx function MENU"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}MENU("menu title")@{ub}

    The procedure associated to the menu is executed. You can specify just
    the first letters of the menu title, (the first matching entry will be
    called).
    Some menu entries can't be called, (see the menu descriptions).
    Some menu titles include spaces, these spaces must be "solid spaces"
    obtained by using the ALT and SPACE keys. This is necessary because
    AmigaGuide doesn't find nodes that include some spaces (or maybe I did
    an error?).

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      MENU ("Quit")   Close all the documents and exit the program.
      MENU ("Copy")   Copy the selected objects in the current clip.

    Return: the menu name if the menu entry was found, else an error
    message is displayed (Incorrect argument value).

    Note: The menu title has to match the localized strings or the
    english built-in string (better: the script will work for any
    country).

  @{i}Example:@{ui} MENU("Copier") in French becomes MENU("Copy") in English.
@ENDNODE
@NODE MESSAGE "ARexx function MESSAGE"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{b}MESSAGE("string")@{ub}

    Display a requester containing the specified message.  This text can
    contain some linefeeds.

  Example:
      MESSAGE("This is one"+CHR(10)+"message.")
@ENDNODE
@NODE MESURE "ARexx function MESURE"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}MESURE(window_dimension)@{ub}

    Return one of dimensions of the current window.  The value which is
    returned depends on the argument:
      equal 0:	co-ordinate of the window's left edge
      equal 1:	co-ordinate of the window's top edge
      equal 2:	width of the window (in pixels)
      equal 3:	height of the window (in pixels)
      equal 4:	maximum width able to be taken by the window
      equal 5:	maximum height able to be taken by the window
      equal 6:	width of screen (ditto @{"SWIDTH" LINK SWIDTH})
      equal 7:	height of screen (ditto @{"SHEIGHT" LINK SHEIGHT}

    If the window is hidden the returned value is always null, except for
    dimensions of the screen, null only if the screen is closed, (when all
    the windows are hidden).
    If the window is iconified the value determining its dimension is
    returned in negative form, (for argument values 0 to 3 inclusive).

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"WINDOW" LINK WINDOW}
@ENDNODE
@NODE MODIF "ARexx function MODIF"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}MODIF@{ub}		Version 2.05 (argument removed)

    Allows you to know if the current window has been modified
    since it was last saved.

    The returned value is null if the diagram was not modified since the
    last save, if it is was modified then it will normally equal 1.

  @{i}Example:@{ui}
      'MODIF(-1)'
      if result~=0 then 'MENU("Save")'

      Another method (faster):
      'IF(MODIF(-1),MENU("Save"),0)'

      This small script can be used for autosaving (see script SauverAuto.AmiCAD)).
@ENDNODE
@NODE MOVE "ARexx function MOVE"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}MOVE(object_number, dx, dy)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to move an object the number of pixels
    specified by the values dx and dy.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS }.
    If it's null, all the selected objects will be moved.

    No value is returned by this function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE NBSHEET "ARexx function NBSHEET"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}NBSHEET(x)@{ub}

    This function has been removed in version 2.05 (see @{"NBSHEETS" LINK NBSHEETS}).
@ENDNODE
@NODE NBSHEETS "ARexx function NBSHEETS"
@TOC GestionĀfenĻtres

    @{b}NBSHEETS("variable_name")@{ub}                  Version 2.05

    This function is used to know how many windows are opened, and
    which ARexx port they are using. It can't be used in local mode.
    The variable name is the name of an ARexx variable that will
    hold the names of the ports:
	variable_name.0 contains the name of the first window port
	variable_name.1 contains the name of the second window port
	Thee number of windows is contained in variable result.

    @{i}Example :@{ui}
	options results
	'NBSHEETS("NAMES")'
	n=result
	do i=0 to n-1
	    address value NAMES.i
	    'MESSAGE("Document "+FILENAME("")+": port 'NAMES.i'")'
	end
@ENDNODE
@NODE NEW "ARexx function NEW"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}NEW("title")@{ub}

    This function has been removed, use @{"NEWSHEET" LINK NEWSHEET} function in place.
@ENDNODE
@NODE NEWSHEET "ARexx function NEWSHEET"
@TOC GestionĀfenĻtres

    @{B}NEWSHEET@{UB}		     Version 2.05

    This function opens a new window. If it succeeds the result is
    positive or nul. If the returned value is negative the function
    failed. The returned value is the number of the new task, the
    ARexx port of this new task is AmiCAD.x (where x is the result).

    The size of the new window is defined by the preferences (document
    size), they can be changed using @{"DIMSHEET" LINK DIMSHEET} function.

    Use the NewWindow script if you want to open a new window, the
    returned value, in some cases, can be no significant if the
    window couln't be opened, this script handles these problems.

    Example:
	call 'NewWindow.AmiCAD' [filename]
	code = result
	if code < 0 then exit
	address value "AmiCAD."||code
    These four lines can open a new window that will take the name
    passed as an argument (filename). The returned code is the one
    returned by function NEWSHEET.
@ENDNODE
@NODE NEXTSEL "ARexx function NEXTSEL"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}NEXTSEL(object_number)@{ub}

    Return the number of the next selected object, according to that which
    is specified in argument.  This function allows you to traverse all the
    selected elements when used in association with @{"FIRSTSEL" LINK FIRSTSEL}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE OBJECTS "ARexx function OBJECTS"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}OBJECTS@{ub}		     Version 2.05 (argument removed)

    This function returns the number of objects that are present on the
    current window.
@ENDNODE
@NODE OPEN "ARexx function OPEN"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}OPEN("name_file")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to load a file in a @{b}new@{ub} window,
    the difference to function @{"LOAD" LINK LOAD } being it also allows
    the loading of several files.
    It is possible to specify generic characters (#?[]) in the name of the
    file, as envisaged under DOS.
    All the diagrams corresponding to this pattern will be loaded.
    A new window is opened for each diagram found, corresponding to the
    request.
    The function returns the number of windows that were opened (v2.07).

  @{i}Examples :@{ui}
      OPEN("Travail:AmiCAD/Schemes/Projet_TV/#?")  asks for the loading of
		      all the files of the directory Projet_TV
      OPEN("#?.sch")  request to load all the files having the sch extension,
		      located in the current directory

  See also: @{"CLOSE" LINK CLOSE}, @{"LOAD" LINK LOAD}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE OUTPUT "ARexx function OUTPUT"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}OUTPUT(nom_connecteur, x, y)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to place an input connector at the
    specified co-ordinates x and y.
    It returns the number of the object which was placed if it succeeds,
    if not it returns 0.

    If the two coordinates are null, the specified string is placed
    under the cursor, and the current mode becomes output connector
    placement.

    The current vertical and horizontal scale are taken into account to
    determine the dimensions of this element, (see @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}, @{"ROTATE" LINK ROTATE},
    @{"SYMMETRY" LINK SYMMETRY}).

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"INPUT" LINK INPUT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE PARTNAME "ARexx function PARTNAME"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}PARTNAME(object_number)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know the name of a component.
    It returns a null string if the selected object is not a component.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"PUTPART" LINK PUTPART}, @{"GETPART" LINK GETPART}
@ENDNODE
@NODE PASTE "ARexx function PASTE"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}PASTE(clip, x, y)@{ub}

    Place the contents of the specified buffer (clip) at the co-ordinates
    given by the arguments x and y.

    No particular value is returned.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"COPY" LINK COPY}, @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PENWIDTH "ARexx function PENWIDTH"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}PENWIDTH(object_number,width)@{ub}

    Allows you to select the width of the feature defining the layout of the
    specified object.  The value of the second parameter must lie between
    1 and 255, if not the function will not have any effect.

    Returned value: Width of the feature used BEFORE the execution of the
    function.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PICKOBJ "ARexx function PICKOBJ"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{b}PICKOBJ("message")@{ub}

    Display the message specified in the titlebar of the window, it then
    awaits a click of the left mouse button in the window.
    Return the number of the object on which the click took place, (0 if
    there isn't one).
    The user can scroll the text using the sliders and associated buttons.
    You can also cancel the operation by pressing on the right mouse button
    or on a key of the keyboard, the returned value is then -1.
@ENDNODE
NODE PINCOL "ARexx function PINCOL"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{B}PINCOL(object_number,pin)@{UB}     @{I}Version 1.4@{UI}

    This function returns the column where is located the specified
    pin. The object must be a component.

    The pin value is not the pin number, when it exists, but the
    order in which the pins are present in a Spice netlist.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"DEVPINS" LINK DEVPINS}, @{"PINLINE" LINK PINLINE}, @{"PINNUM" LINK PINNUM}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PINLINE "ARexx function PINLINE"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{B}PINLINE(object_number,pin)@{UB}    @{I}Version 1.4@{UI}

    This function returns the line where is located the specified
    pin. The object must be a component.

    The pin value is not the pin number, when it exists, but the
    order in which the pins are present in a Spice netlist.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"DEVPINS" LINK DEVPINS}, @{"PINCOL" LINK PINCOL}, @{"PINNUM" LINK PINNUM}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PINNUM "ARexx function PINNUM"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{B}PINNUM(object_number,pin)@{UB}      @{I}Version 1.4@{UI}

    This function returns the number of the specified pin.
    The object must be a component.

    The pin value is not the pin number, when it exists, but the
    order in which the pins are present in a Spice netlist.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"DEVPINS" LINK DEVPINS}, @{"PINCOL" LINK PINCOL}, @{"PINLINE" LINK PINLINE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PRINT "ARexx function PRINT"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}PRINT(ratio, rotation)@{ub}

    @{"Print" LINK "PrintĀpage"} the diagram, taking account of the
    arguments: ratio (factor of enlarging, must be equal to or higher than
    1) and rotation (if equal to 0, the diagram is printed as it is displayed
    on the screen, if equal to 1, the diagram is printed with a rotation of
    90 degrees).

    Return 0 if all occurs well, an error code in the contrary case.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PUTPART "ARexx function PUTPART"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}PUTPART("name_component", x, y)@{ub}

    Place the component specified at the co-ordinates given by the following
    arguments.
    Warning: the reference and the value are not placed, use functions
    @{"SETREF" LINK SETREF} and @{"SETVAL" LINK SETVAL} or @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF} and @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL} for that.

    The currant vertical and horizontal scale are taken into account to
    determine the dimensions of this element (see @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}, @{"ROTATE" LINK ROTATE},
    @{"SYMMETRY" LINK SYMMETRY}).

    This function returns the code of the object which was placed if it
    succeeds, if not it returns 0.

    Version 1.6:
    If the coordinnates x and y are equal to -1, the specified component
    becomes the current component, when using the @{"Drawing/place component" LINK "PlaceĀcomponent"}.
    This function replaces the old @{"GETPART" LINK GETPART} function.

  See also: @{"GETPART" LINK GETPART}, @{"PARTNAME" LINK PARTNAME}
@ENDNODE
@NODE READCONV "ARexx function READCONV"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}READCONV(object_number)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know what the type of symbol used to
    display a component is.
    It returns -1 if the selected object is not a component, 0 if this
    component is displayed normally or 1 if it is the alternate symbol which
    is used.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If it's null, the current mode is returned.

  See also: @{"CONVERT" LINK CONVERT}, menu Drawing/@{"Alternate symbol" LINK "AlternateĀsymbol"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE READDEF "ARexx function READDEF"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}READDEF("function")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know the definition associated with
    a function.  The name of the function passed in the argument must appear
    in capital letters, between brackets.  This function must of course
    have been defined beforehand using function DEF, if not a null string is
    returned.
    You cannot read the internal definitions, like ABS, ASK, etc...

  @{i}Example:@{ui}
      READDEF("CIRCLE")   returns the definition associated with function CIRCLE,
			  if it exists.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"DEF" LINK DEF}
@ENDNODE
@NODE READDEV "ARexx function READDEV"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}READDEV(object_number)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to know which is the gate or the
    circuit used by a component.
    It returns -1 if the selected object is not a component, 0 if this
    component includes only one circuit or the number of the selected
    circuit, (then it will be equal to or higher than 1).

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SETDEV" LINK SETDEV}, @{"GETDEVS" LINK GETDEVS}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE READMAP "ARexx function READMAP"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}READMAP("key combination")@{ub}

    This function returns a string with the definition associated to the
    argument.
    If there is no definition an empty string is returned.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      READMAP("shift-ctrl-a")
      READMAP("CTRL-i")
      READMAP("ALT-Ą")
      EXEC(READMAP("F1"))       Executes the associate command of key F1

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"MAP" LINK MAP}, @{"UNMAP" LINK UNMAP}
@ENDNODE
@NODE READTEXT "ARexx function READTEXT"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}READTEXT(object_number)@{ub}

    Return the text associated with an object, this object can be an
    element of text, or a connector (input or output).
    If this text does not exist or if the object is of a different type
    the function returns a null string.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SETTEXT" LINK SETTEXT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REMLIB "ARexx function REMLIB"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}REMLIB("library_name")@{ub}

    Remove the specified library from memory.

    Warning:  no element of this library must be present on
    an opened document, or this operation will fail.

    This operation can make it possible to gain memory, by removing for
    example, a library which is not used any more.

    You can also use the button "Remove" in the "Loading component"
    requester.

  @{i}Example :@{ui} REMLIB("Symboles TTL")

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"LOADLIB" LINK LOADLIB}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQFILE "ARexx function REQFILE"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{b}REQFILE("title_requester","path","file")@{ub}

    Open a file requester with the specified title and in the specified
    path.  This path must correspond to that of a directory or a volume.

    Return the full name of the selected file or a null string if the user
    clicks on the Cancel button.

    @{i}Example:@{ui}
    REQFILE("Choose a file","Work:AmiCAD","")
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQLIST "ARexx function REQLIST"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{b}REQLIST (title, entry1, ...)@{ub}          @{i}Version 2.04@{ui}

	This function opens a requester with the specified title, the
	entries are displayed in a listview, the number of the selected
	entry is returned if the user clicks on one of them (1 for the
	first item). If the user clicks on Cancel or closes the window,
	-1 is returned.

	If the requester couldn't be opened, 0 is returned.
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQSHEET "ARexx function REQSHEET"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}REQSHEET("title")@{ub}              Version 2.05 (modified)

    This function makes it possible to choose, using a requester, a
    diagram among those which are loaded in memory.
    The title is displayed in the first line.
    The name of the ARexx port of the selected diagram is returned.
    If the user presses on the right mouse button or if a problem occurs, a
    null string is returned.
    Operation is similar to that obtained after a double click on the
    @{"right mouse button" LINK Sheets}, however with this function you can choose
    the title displayed in the heading.
@ENDNODE
@NODE REQUEST "ARexx function REQUEST"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{b}REQUEST("title")@{ub}

    Display a requester with the specified text, (maximum of thirteen lines,
    separated by linefeeds), and two buttons YES and NO.
    If the user clicks on the button YES or uses the Enter key, this function
    returns 1.
    If the user clicks on the button NO or uses the ESC key, the returned
    value is 0.
    In the event of a problem, (lack of memory for example), the returned
    value is negative.
@ENDNODE
@NODE RESET "ARexx function RESET"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}RESET(variable,...)@{ub}

    This function is identical to function @{"INIT" LINK INIT}, however the type is not
     re-initialized.
    If @{"variable" LINK Variable} is of the numerical type it takes value 0,
    if it is a character string it becomes a null string ("").
    The number of arguments is unspecified.

  @{i}Example:@{ui}
      RESET(A,B,C)

  See also: @{"INIT" LINK INIT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE REXXPORT "ARexx function REXXPORT"
@TOC GestionĀfenĻtres

    @{b}REXXPORT("nom_fichier")@{ub}                  Version 2.05

    This function returns the name of the ARexx port associated to a
    document, if it's present in memory. A null string is returned if
    the document doesn't exists.
    The argument doesn't needs to be the full path name (optional). If
    it's a null string, the name of the current window is returned.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"NBSHEETS" LINK NBSHEETS}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ROTATE "ARexx function ROTATE"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}ROTATE(object_number, rotations)@{ub}

    Fact of turning the specified object the number of quarters of
    specified turn.
    If the object number is null, it is the current mode of placement which
    is affected:  the placements carried out then will take account of this
    new position, that it is by macro (@{"PUTPART" LINK PUTPART } for example) or a
    menu.
    This function returns 0 if the operation failed, (for lack of space
    for example), if not it returns 1.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SYMMETRY" LINK SYMMETRY}, @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SAVE "ARexx function SAVE"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}SAVE("file_name")@{ub}

    Save the document under the specified name.  If the file exists already
    no warning is given.
    Return 1 if no problem occurs, if not 0.
    An info file comprising an icon is created if the menu
    @{"Preferences/Save icon" LINK "SaveĀicon"} is marked, a file comprising
    the ".bis" extension is created if the menu @{"Preferences/Backup file" LINK "BackupĀfile"}
    is marked.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SAVECOPY" LINK SAVECOPY}, @{"SAVEICON" LINK SAVEICON}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SAVEALL "ARexx function SAVEALL"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}SAVEALL@{ub}	    Version 2.05 (argument removed)

    This function is used to save all the documents that are present in
    memory in the Undo cache.  So you can later cancel the changes made by
    an ARexx script.
    The function must be called before you make any change to the document.
    The user can cancel the operations done by the script, (or macro), using
    the @{"Undo menu" LINK Undo}.

    @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      SAVEALL(-1)     saves the current document
      SAVEALL(0)      saves the first document
      SAVEALL(1)      saves the second document
@ENDNODE
@NODE SAVECLIP "ARexx function SAVECLIP"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}SAVECLIP(unit,"filename")@{ub}

    This function is used to save the specified clip in a file.
    Naturelly the clip must have been initialized using the @{"COPY" LINK COPY}
    function, for example.
    If the file name doesn't include any path, the file will be saved in the
    path defined by the @{"CLIPS" LINK CLIPS} tooltype or the @{"CLIPPATH" LINK CLIPPATH} function.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"LOADCLIP" LINK LOADCLIP}, @{"CLIPUNIT" LINK CLIPUNIT}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SAVECOPY "ARexx function SAVECOPY"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}SAVECOPY(1/0/-1)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to set, like the menu
    @{"Preferences/Backup file" LINK "BackupĀfile"}, whether a copy of the
    diagram will be created at the time of saving of the diagram.
    This function returns 1 if the menu was marked BEFORE the execution of
    the function, or 0 if it wasn't it.
    If the argument is -1 the menu state is toggled.

    To read the state of the menu without modifying it, use the command
    SAVECOPY(-2).

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SAVEICON" LINK SAVEICON}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SAVEICON "ARexx function SAVEICON"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}SAVEICON(1/0/-1)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to set, like the menu
    @{"Preferences/Save icon" LINK "SaveĀicon"}, whether an icon will be
    created at the time of saving of the diagram.
    This function returns 1 if the menu was marked BEFORE the execution of
    the function, or 0 if it wasn't.
    If the argument is -1 the menu state is toggled.

    To read the state of the menu without modifying it, use the command
    SAVEICON(-2).

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SAVECOPY" LINK SAVECOPY}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SAVEIFF "ARexx function SAVEIFF"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}SAVEIFF("file name",ratio)@{ub}

    The current document is saved using the IFF format (2 colors).
    A 0 is returned if it worked.
    Version 2.01: the ratio is given in percentage (equal to 100 to have
    a normal size).

    @{I}Example :@{UI}
    SAVEIFF("Work:Images/Schķma_amplificateur", 200)

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"Project menu/Save IFF" LINK "SaveĀIFF"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SAVEKEYS "ARexx function SAVEKEYS"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{B}SAVEKEYS("filename")@{UB}

    This function has been removed from version 2.05.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SAVEPREF "ARexx function SAVEPREF"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}SAVEPREF("filename")@{ub}

    This function has been removed from version 2.05.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCREEN "ARexx function SCREEN"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}SCREEN (mode, width, height,"font",font_size)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to choose the resolution of the screen
    of AmiCAD without having to use the ASL requester, as with the menu
    "Preferences/Screen mode".  Moreover you can specify which will be the
    font used for the menus, requesters, etc...
    The name of the font must be complete, including the extension ".font".
    However it will be necessary for you to know the values associated with
    the various types of screen, a simple means to find out is to display
    them with function @{"SCRMODE" LINK SCRMODE}, by typing the command
    =SCRMODE into the menu @{"Macros/Direct" LINK Direct} requester.

      Thus the following values are possible:
      - 561188 for a screen in super interlaced resolution (SUPER72)
      - 561152 for a screen in SUPER72 high resolution.
      - 233509 for a screen MultiScan interlaced Productivity
      - 167936 for a screen STAKE high resolution
      - 135168 for a screen STAKE low resolution

    The function returns the code in force BEFORE its execution.

    The program does not correctly manage, for the moment, dimensions
    higher than the visible portion of the screen.

    The screen always includes 16 colours.

    @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      SCREEN(561188,800,600, "courier.font",15) "normal" screen (Super 72)
      SCREEN(135168,320,200, "topaz.font",8)    low resolution screen (for "closeup")

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SCRMODE" LINK SCRMODE}, @{"SHEIGHT" LINK SHEIGHT}, @{"SWIDTH" LINK SWIDTH}, @{"FONTNAME" LINK FONTNAME}, @{"FONTSIZE" LINK FONTSIZE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SCRMODE "ARexx function SCRMODE"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}SCRMODE@{ub}

    This function returns the value associated with the mode with current
    screen.
    It does not need any argument.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SCREEN" LINK SCREEN}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SECURITY "ARexx function SECURITY"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}SECURITY(number_of_loops)@{ub}

    This function determines the maximum number of loops able to be carried
    out by one of the functions @{"FOR" LINK FOR} or @{"WHILE" LINK WHILE}.
    This makes it possible to exit endless loops rather simply.
    The default value is equal to 500.	You can enter a value going from
    1 until 2^31-1 (2147483647).
    The function returns the value in progress before its execution.

    You can give this function an argument of great value without fearing
    blocking, it is now possible to stop a loop while pressing
    simultaneously on the keys CTRL, ALT and ESC.

    If the value passed in argument is null only the current value is
    returned, without modification.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SELECT "ARexx function SELECT"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{b}SELECT("text")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to open a requester comprising a variable
    number of buttons, each one using a text chosen by the user.
    If the user clicks on one of these buttons, the function returns the row
    of the button, (while starting with value 1 for the first, 2 for the
    second, etc...).

    The format of the text passed in argument must be the following:
	- a first line, displayed in title,
	- a second line, corresponding to the text of the first button,
	- a third line, corresponding to the text of the second button,
	- and so on, as many lines than of buttons...

    Each line is separated from following by a linefeed (CHR(10)).

    If the returned value is negative or null, the user pressed on the right
    mouse button or the Esc key, or the requester could not be opened.

    @{i}Example:@{ui}
      SELECT("Number of circuits?"+CHR(10)+"10 circuits"+CHR(10)+"20 circuits"+CHR(10)+"Undetermined")
@ENDNODE
@NODE SELFILE "ARexx function SELFILE"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}SELFILE("file_name")@{ub}

    This function has been removed from version 2.05.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SELSHEET "ARexx function SELSHEET"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}SELSHEET(window)@{ub}

    This function has been removed from version 2.05.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETARRAY "ARexx function SETARRAY"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}SETARRAY(arrayname,ord,value)@{ub}

    This function sets a value to an object of an array. Ord
    must be included between 0 and the array size minus 1.
    If ord is lower than 0, ALL the objects of the array are
    sets to the specified value.
    The value must always be of the same type (integer or string)
    for a given array.

    @{i}Example:@{ui}
	'DIMARRAY(N,100)'
	'FOR(I=0,I<100,SETARRAY(N,I,I*2),I=I+1)'
	'GETARRAY(N,50)'            return 100
	'SETARRAY(N,-1,0)'
	'GETARRAY(N,50)'            return 0

    See also: @{"ARRAYDIM" LINK ARRAYDIM}, @{"DIMARRAY" LINK DIMARRAY}, @{"DELARRAY" LINK DELARRAY}, @{"GETARRAY" LINK GETARRAY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETCOLOR "ARexx function SETCOLOR"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}SETCOLOR(colour,red_level,green_level,blue_level)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to choose the colour of the AmiCAD
    screen.
    The number corresponding to this colour must lie between 0
    and 15 inclusive, (the screen has 16 colours).
    The level of the colours are long words, 32 bits. To specify white,
    pass three arguments equal to 0xFFFFFFFF, to bring a level of colour
    to an intermediate level, pass an argument of value 0x7FFFFFFF.

    No value is returned by this function.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETDEV "ARexx function SETDEV"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{b}SETDEV(object_number, circuit_number)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to choose the number of the circuit or
    gate for a component that is comprised of several of them.
    It is useful for the circuits comprised of multiple gates like TTL 7400,
    for example.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If it's null, the current placement mode is affected (the next component
    that will be placed will have this number).

    The function can return three possible results:
       - 0  if the specified object is not a component,
       - 1  if the operation succeeded,
       - -1 if the number of the circuit is incorrect.

  See also: @{"READDEV" LINK READDEV}, @{"GETDEVS" LINK GETDEVS}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETFILL "ARexx function SETFILL"
@TOC PlacementĀobjets

    @{B}SETFILL(0/1/-1)@{UB}

    Define the filling mode when drawing boxes, triangles or ellipses @{I}(v2.0).@{UI}

    If argument is 1, the objects will be filled,  if it's 0 they will
    not. If it's -1 the mode is unchanged.
    The function returns the value that was used @{b}before@{ub} execution of the command.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETGRID "ARexx function SETGRID"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}SETGRID(grid_step)@{ub}

    Define the size of the grid used to place the components on the diagram.
    Note that this function does not update the grid on the screen, which
    can pose problems, use the menu "Drawing/Redraw all" if you wish that
    it be updated, by using for example the following command:
      SETGRID(15):MENU("Redraw all")

    Returned value:  The step value used before the execution of the command.

    Use the command SETGRID(0) to know the current grid step without
    modifying it.

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"SNAPGRID" LINK SNAPGRID}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETLABEL "ARexx function SETLABEL"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{b}SETLABEL(object_number,"Label")@{ub}

    The specified label (a string char) is affected to the specified
    object. If this object already had a label, it's replaced.
    Naturely, this object must be a line.

    The object number of the added or modified object is returned
    if the operation succeeded (0 else). This number is the same
    that the returned value of the GETLABEL function (Version 2.08).

    @{I}Example :@{UI}	  SETLABEL(FIRSTSEL,"Label1")

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"LINKLAB" LINK LINKLAB}, @{"UNLINK" LINK UNLINK}, @{"GETLABEL" LINK GETLABEL}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETMASK "ARexx function SETMASK"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{b}SETMASK(object_number,"PCB mask")@{ub}

    The specified value (string) is linked to the specified
    object. If this object already had a linked PCB mask,
    this last one is replaced. The first argument must be
    a component.

    The object number of the PCB mask (added or modified) is
    returned if the operation succeeds (0 else).
    This number is the same that the result of the GETMASK
    function (Version 2.09).

    @{I}Example :@{UI}	  SETMASK(FIRSTSEL,"Rķsistance/Res-small")

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"GETMASK" LINK GETMASK}, @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF}, @{"SETVAL" LINK SETVAL}, @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETORTHO "ARexx function SETORTHO"
@TOC PlacementĀobjets

    @{B}SETORTHO(action)@{UB}

    Define if the lines will be drawn using 45░ angles or not, when they
    are placed by the user.

    See also menu @{"Drawing/Orthogonal mode" LINK "OrthogonalĀmode"}.

    If action is equal to 1, the menu will be marked,
    if action is equal to 0, the menu is unmarked,
    if action is equal to -1, the menu state is toggled.
    For any other value nothing happens.

    Returned value: the value used before the execution of the command.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETPINS "ARexx function SETPINS"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}SETPINS(object_number,ON/OFF)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to determine whether the pin numbers of
    a component will be displayed or not.
    If the second argument is higher than 0, the display is confirmed, if
    it is equal to 0, the display is removed, if it is less than 0 nothing
    is changed.

    The returned value is equal to 1 if the display was validated BEFORE
    the application of the function, 0 in the contrary case.

    If the specified object is not a component, the returned value is always
    equal to -1.

    @{i}Example:@{ui}
	SETPINS(FIRSTSEL, -1) returns the state of the 1st object selected
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETPULL "ARexx function SETPULL"
@TOC GestionĀprķfķrences

    @{b}SETPULL(0/1/-1)@{ub}

    If the argument is 0, the lines will not be pulled by
    components when moving them, if it's 1 they will be moved.
    If the argument is -1, the function has no effect.

    The returned value is the value associated with the current mode
    before execution of the function (0 if no moves, 1 if moves are
    validated).

    To toggle the current mode, you can use the @{"Pull lines" LINK "PullĀlines"} menu
    or the next macro :
	SETPULL(IF(SETPULL(-1),0,1))
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETREF "ARexx function SETREF"
@TOC GestionĀdesĀobjets

    @{b}SETREF(object_number,"reference")@{ub}

    The specified value, (in the form of a character string), is allocated to
    the specified object.  If the specified object already had a reference,
    it is replaced.

    @{i}Example:@{ui}
      SETREF(FIRSTSEL,"R2")

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF}, @{"SETVAL" LINK SETVAL}, @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETSCALE "ARexx function SETSCALE"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}SETSCALE(object_number, horizontal_scale, vertical_scale)@{ub}

    This function is used to modify the scale of an object.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If it's set to 0, the function sets the current scales, used to place
    new objects, like the menu @{"Drawing/Place component" LINK "PlaceĀcomponent"}.

    These values can also be set using the menu @{"Preferences/Vertical scale" LINK "Vertical"}
    and @{"Preferences/Horizontal scale" LINK "Horizontal"}.

    If one of the scale values is set to 0, it's value will not be changed.

    This function returns 1 if it succeeded, 0 if it didn't.

    If a script has to change one of the current placement scales, it is
    good to set this scales to their first value.  You can do this using
    the next example script :

	/* We want to use horizontal scale X and vertical scale Y */
	'_EH_=HSCALE(0):_EV_=VSCALE(0):SETSCALE(0,X,Y)'
	...
	'SETSCALE(0,_EH_,_EV_)'

    @{I}See also :@{UI} @{"HSCALE" LINK HSCALE}, @{"VSCALE" LINK VSCALE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETTEXT "ARexx function SETTEXT"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}SETTEXT(object_number,"string")@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to set the text associated with an
    object.
    This object must be of the type text, value or reference of a component,
    or a connector.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    The returned value is equal to 1 if the function succeeded, if not it
    is null.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"READTEXT" LINK READTEXT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SETVAL "ARexx function SETVAL"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}SETVAL(object_number,"value")@{ub}

    The specified value, (in the form of a character string), is allocated to
    the specified object.  If the specified object had already a value, it
    is replaced.

    @{i}Example:@{ui}
      SETVAL(FIRSTSEL,"100k")

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL}, @{"SETREF" LINK SETREF}, @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SGN "ARexx function SGN"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}SGN(number)@{ub}

    Return 1 if the argument is positive, -1 if it is negative, zero if it
    is null.
@ENDNODE
@NODE SHEIGHT "ARexx function SHEIGHT"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}SHEIGHT@{ub}

    This function returns the height of the current screen.
    It does not require any argument.

  See also: @{"SCREEN" LINK SCREEN}, @{"SWIDTH" LINK SWIDTH}, @{"SCRMODE" LINK SCRMODE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SNAPGRID "Fonction ARexx SNAPGRID"
@TOC PlacementĀobjets

    @{B}SNAPGRID(action)@{UB}

    This function sets the placement mode of the objects by the user.

    If action is equal to 1, the menu will be marked,
    if action is equal to 0, the menu will be unmarked,
    if action is -1, the menu state is toggled.
    For any other value nothing happens.

    The menu state before execution of the function is returned.

    @{I}See also:@{UI} @{"SETGRID" LINK SETGRID}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE STOBACK "ARexx function STOBACK"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}STOBACK@{ub}

    This function moves the AmiCAD screen to the background.
    It does not require any argument.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"STOFRONT" LINK STOFRONT} @{"WTOBACK" LINK WTOBACK} @{"WTOFRONT" LINK WTOFRONT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE STOFRONT "ARexx function STOFRONT"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}STOFRONT@{ub}

    This function moves the AmiCAD screen to the foreground.
    It does not require any argument.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"STOBACK" LINK STOBACK} @{"WTOBACK" LINK WTOBACK} @{"WTOFRONT" LINK WTOFRONT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE STR "ARexx function STR"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}STR(number)@{ub}

    Return the character string corresponding to a number.
    The base used for conversion is base 10 (decimal).
@ENDNODE
@NODE SWIDTH "ARexx function SWIDTH"
@TOC "GestionĀprķfķrences"

    @{b}SWIDTH@{ub}

    This function returns the width of the current screen.
    It does not require any argument.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SCREEN" LINK SCREEN}, @{"SHEIGHT" LINK SHEIGHT}, @{"SCRMODE" LINK SCRMODE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE SYMMETRY "ARexx function SYMMETRY"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}SYMMETRY(object_number, position)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to mirror an object about it's vertical
    axis, (or its horizontal axis, if it's rotated one or three quarters of
    turn).

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If this number is null, the function modifies the way of placing
    components, (menu "Drawing/Place component").

    The position argument can take three values:
       - equal to 1:   symmetry is carried out,
       - equal to 0:   no symmetry,
       - equal to -1:  position reversal.

    The returned value is equal to 1 if there was a modification of the
    position of the object, 0 in the contrary case.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"ROTATE" LINK ROTATE}, @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE TEST "ARexx function TEST"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}TEST(object_number)@{ub}

    Allows you to find out if an object is selected or not.
    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    The function returns 1 if the object is selected, 0 in the contrary case.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TIME "ARexx function TIME"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}TIME(seconds)@{ub}

    Return the current hour, if the argument is non null, the seconds are
    included.

    @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      TIME(0)                   returns 23:24
      TIME(1)                   returns 23:24:27
      WRITE(TIME(1),0,0)        writes the current time "under" the cursor

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"DATE" LINK DATE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE TITLE "ARexx function TITLE"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}TITLE("title")@{ub}

    Specify the title of the current window.  If the argument is a null
    string, the title reverts to it's normal state, i.e. the name of the file
    reappears there.
    This function makes it possible to announce a long operation by warning
    the user, without blocking the window or the program.

    @{i}Example of script:@{ui}
      'TITLE("Processing...")'
      'TITLE("")'                  gives the normal title
@ENDNODE
@NODE TOOLBAR "ARexx function TOOLBAR"
@TOC GestionĀprķfķrences

    @{B}TOOLBAR("filename")@{UB}

    The specified toolbar is loaded. The file format must be IFF.
    Its icon must have some tooltypes :
	-COLUMNS: number of icons on a line,
	-LINES: number of icons lines,
	-COMMAND(x,y): command associated to the icon located
	at the specified coordinates (a command for an icon).
	-XBAR: window left edge (optional),
	-YBAR: window top edge (optional).
    This function uses the iff.library to load the images.

    This function can be used with a null string ("") as argument,
    if called like that, the toolbars already opened are sent
    to the foregound.

    To @{B}create a new toolbar@{UB}, create an image with a
    program like PPaint, DPaint or any other one. Save this image
    as a brush, keeping one pixel on the borders (all the icons
    must have the same dimensions). Then you can edit the
    image tooltypes, adding the COLUMNS and LINES tooltypes
    as a minimum. The commands can then be edited using
    AmiCAD : load the toolbar, select it using the left mouse
    button, then click on any icon with the right mouse button.
    A requester is opened, choose a button to select the action
    you want to do (edit, copy, paste, shift or save commands)
    Don't remember @{b}to save@{ub} the result when all is
    working like you want.

    @{b}Warning:@{ub} if you are using a paint program to edit the image,
    be carefull : some of these programs are clearing all the
    tooltypes when saving your work, if so, work on a copy of
    the image.

    This function returns 0 if loading the image was fine (version
    2.05).
@ENDNODE
@NODE TRIANGLE "ARexx function TRIANGLE"
@TOC PlacementĀobjets

    @{B}TRIANGLE(x0,y0,x1,y1,x2,y2)@{UB}

    This function draws a triangle using the specified coordinates.
    The line width uses the current drawing mode (see @{"DRAWMODE" LINK DRAWMODE})
    and the filling mode (see @{"SETFILL" LINK SETFILL}).

    The number of the object that was created is returned (0 if error).

    Use function @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS} to know the coordinates of an
    existing triangle.
@ENDNODE
@NODE TXHEIGHT "ARexx function TXHEIGHT"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}TXHEIGHT("text")@{ub}

    Return the height of the specified text, in pixels.  This function
    takes into account the current scale, as well as the mode of placement,
    (possible rotation).
    In all the cases it is the occupied vertical space which is returned.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"TXWIDTH" LINK TXWIDTH}
@ENDNODE
@NODE TXWIDTH "ARexx function TXWIDTH"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}TXWIDTH("text")@{ub}

    Return the width of the specified text, in pixels.	This function
    takes into account the current scale, as well as the mode of placement,
    (possible rotation).
    In all the cases it is the occupied horizontal space which is returned.

    This function is useful to center a text in a rectangle:
      options results
      text="Test text"
      xx=100;y=100
      'TXWIDTH("'text'")'
      l=result
      'TXHEIGHT("'text'")'
      h=result
      'DRAW('xx','y','xx+l','y'):DRAW('xx+l','y','xx+l','y+h')'
      'DRAW('xx+l','y+h','xx','y+h'):DRAW('xx','y+h','xx','y')'
      'WRITE("'text'",'xx','y+h')'

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"TXHEIGHT" LINK TXHEIGHT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE TYPE "ARexx function TYPE"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}TYPE(object_number)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to find out the nature of an object.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    The returned value depends on the type of the character:
      - equal to 1:   it is a @{b}component@{ub}
      - equal to 2:   it is a @{b}normal wire connection@{ub}
      - equal to 3:   it is @{b}an arc of a circle@{ub}
      - equal to 4:   it is a @{b}text@{ub}
      - equal to 5:   it is a @{b}reference of a component@{ub}
      - equal to 6:   it is a @{b}value of a component@{ub} (or its type)
      - equal to 7:   it is a @{b}connection@{ub}
      - equal to 8:   it is a feature in @{b}dotted lines@{ub}
      - equal to 9:   it is a @{b}bus@{ub}
      - equal to 10:  it is an @{b}ellipse@{ub}
      - equal to 11:  it is an @{b}input connector@{ub}
      - equal to 12:  it is an @{b}output connector@{ub}
      - equal to 15:  it is a @{b}double line@{ub}
      - equal to 21:  it is a @{b}personalized line@{ub} (unspecified width)
      - equal to 22:  it is a @{B}box@{UB}
      - equal to 24:  it is a @{B}filled box@{UB}
      - equal to 26:  it is a @{B}triangle@{UB}
      - equal to 27:  it is a @{B}filled triangle@{UB}
      - equal to 28:  it is a @{b}label@{ub} (Version 2.08).

    You can thus define functions which recognize the objects:
      DEF COMPONENT(O) = IF (TYPE(O) == 1, 1, 0)
      DEF WIRE(O) = IF (TYPE(O) == 2, 1, 0)
      DEF CONNECTOR(O) = IF ((TYPE(O)==11) | (TYPE(O)==12), 1,0)
      DEF LINED(O) = IF ((TYPE(O)==2) | (TYPE(O)==8) | (TYPE(O)==9) | (TYPE(O)==15) |  (TYPE(O)==21), 1, 0)

    Each one of these functions returns 1 if the character is of the type
    tested, if not they return 0.
@ENDNODE
@NODE UNGROUP "Arexx function UNGROUP"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}UNGROUP(group)@{ub}                 @{I}Version 1.4@{UI}

    The group whose number is specified as the argument is dissolved.

    Returns the number of objects that were in the group.

  See also: @{"GROUP" LINK GROUP}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE UNLINK "ARexx function UNLINK"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}UNLINK(object_number)@{ub}

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    This function makes it possible to break the links existing between a
    component and it's reference, or it's value. The object number can be
    the component, the reference or the value. The function returns the
    number of links that were broken.
    If the specified object is not a component returned value is equal to -1.

    @{b}Version 2.08:@{ub} this function also permits to break the link
    between a label and a line. The object number can be any of the two
    objects : the label or the line.

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      UNLINK(FIRSTSEL)
      UNLINK(PICKOBJ("Click on a component"))

  @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"LINKVAL" LINK LINKVAL}, @{"LINKREF" LINK LINKREF}
@ENDNODE
@NODE UNLOCK "ARexx function UNLOCK"
@TOC Interactivitķ

    @{b}UNLOCK@{ub}	    Version 2.05 (argument removed)

    Cancel the locking of the current window, initiated by function @{"LOCK" LINK LOCK}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE UNMAP "ARexx function UNMAP"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}UNMAP("key combination")@{ub}

    This function deletes a programmed macro associated with a key
    combination.
    The ALT, SHIFT and CTRL can be used to define the combination, (one of
    them must be used, except for the function keys).

  @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      UNMAP("shift-ctrl-a")
      UNMAP("ctrl-shift-a")
      UNMAP("CTRL-)")
      UNMAP("ALT-Ą")
      UNMAP("F2")

  @{i}See also:@{ui}
      @{"MAP" LINK MAP}, @{"READMAP" LINK READMAP}
@ENDNODE
@NODE UNMARK "ARexx function UNMARK"
@TOC "GestionĀblocs"

    @{b}UNMARK(object_number,...)@{ub}

    Cancel the marking of the specified objects.

    The object numbers must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    Return the number of selections having been cancelled.

    If argument value is -1, then all selected components are unmarked,
    the function returns 0.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"MARK" LINK MARK}, @{"MARKZONE" LINK MARKZONE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE VAL "ARexx function VAL"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}VAL("string")@{ub}

    Return the numerical value corresponding to the character string passed
    in the argument.
    Only the characters corresponding to integers are taken into account.
    The number must appear in decimal form, except if it is preceded by the
    prefix $, which announces that it is in hexadecimal form.

    @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      VAL("14")   returns 14
      VAL("14.3") returns 14
      VAL("$5F")  returns 95 (the $ specifies a hexadecimal string)

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"STR" LINK STR}
@ENDNODE
@NODE VERSION "ARexx function VERSION"
@TOC Divers

    @{b}VERSION(arg)@{ub}

    This function returns the current version number of the program,
    the argument can be any value (version 2.03).
    This function can be used to test if a program can execute a script or
    not.

    @{i}Example of script:@{ui}
      'VERSION(0)'
      if result < 2.00 then do
	'MESSAGE("This program version"+CHR(10)+"can''t do this job!")'
	exit
      end
      ...
@ENDNODE
@NODE VISIBLE "ARexx function VISIBLE"

    @{b}VISIBLE(x,y)@{ub}

    This function makes it possible to see a point in the window,
    when the screen is too small to fit all the document. So it's
    possible to see a component, by example.
@ENDNODE
@NODE VSCALE "ARexx function VSCALE"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}VSCALE(object_number)@{ub}

    This function returns the vertical scale value of the specified object.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.
    If the argument is null, the current vertical scale is returned (v2.07).

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"HSCALE" LINK HSCALE}, @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE WHEIGHT "ARexx function WHEIGHT"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}WHEIGHT(window_index)@{ub}            Version 2.05 (argument removed)

    The returned value corresponds to the width of the document, in pixels.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"WWIDTH" LINK WWIDTH}, @{"MESURE" LINK MESURE}, @{"WINDOW" LINK WINDOW}, @{"SCREEN" LINK SCREEN}, @{"DIMSHEET" LINK DIMSHEET}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WHILE "ARexx function WHILE"
@TOC Maths

    @{b}WHILE(end,action1,...)@{ub}

    Is identical in function to @{"FOR" LINK FOR}, it just misses this
    functions first argument.
    The initialization of @{"variables" LINK Variable} or the units tested
    will thus have had to be carried out before.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"SECURITY" LINK SECURITY}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WIDTH "ARexx function WIDTH"
@TOC "GestionĀdesĀobjets"

    @{b}WIDTH(object_number)@{ub}

    Returns the width of the specified object, in pixels.

    The object number must be set between the values 1 and @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"HEIGHT" LINK HEIGHT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WINDOW "ARexx function WINDOW"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}WINDOW(x, y, width, height)@{ub}

    This function allows you to redimension the current window, or to move
    it.
    The first two arguments correspond to the co-ordinates of the top left
    corner of the window on the screen.  The two following arguments
    determine its dimensions.

    Warning: This function functions only for "normal" windows.
    For iconified windows, only co-ordinate x can be modified, (to move the
    windows).
    The hidden windows cannot, naturally, be modified but you can specify
    command WINDOW(-1, -1, -1, -1) to allow their reopening.

    If you do not want to modify one or more these parameters and you do not
    know their value, give them a negative value (-1).
    If the arguments are too large or aberrant values, the program will try
    to cure it as well as possible.

    The returned value is equal to the number of values having been taken
    into account.

    @{i}Examples:@{ui}
      WINDOW(0,0,-1,-1)       moves the window in top on the left of the
			      screen without modifying its dimensions.
      WINDOW(-1, -1, 200, 50) exchange dimensions of the window

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"MEASURE" LINK MESURE}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WRITE "ARexx function WRITE"
@TOC "PlacementĀobjets"

    @{b}WRITE("string", x, y)@{ub}

    Place a text at the specified coordinates. If the coordinates are null,
    the string is placed under the cursor and the user can click anywhere
    to place it.

    The current horizontal and vertical scales are used (see @{"SETSCALE" LINK SETSCALE},
    @{"ROTATE" LINK ROTATE}, @{"SYMMETRY" LINK SYMMETRY}).

    If the placement is OK, this function returns the number of the new
    object, else 0.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"READTEXT" LINK READTEXT}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE WTOBACK "ARexx function WTOBACK"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}WTOBACK@{ub}	   Version 2.05 (argument removed)

    Send the current window to the background.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"WTOFRONT" LINK WTOFRONT}, @{"STOBACK" LINK STOBACK}, @{"STOFRONT" LINK STOFRONT}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WTOFRONT "ARexx function WTOFRONT"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}WTOFRONT(window)@{ub}       Version 2.05 (argument removed)

    Send the current window to the foreground.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"WTOBACK" LINK WTOBACK}
@ENDNODE
@NODE WWIDTH "ARexx function WWIDTH"
@TOC "GestionĀfenĻtres"

    @{b}WWIDTH@{ub}		Version 2.05 (argument removed)

    Return the working width of the curent window.
    The returned value corresponds to the height of the document, in pixels.

    @{i}See also:@{ui} @{"WHEIGHT" LINK WHEIGHT}, @{"MESURE" LINK MESURE}, @{"WINDOW" LINK WINDOW}, @{"SCREEN" LINK SCREEN}, @{"DIMSHEET" LINK DIMSHEET}
@ENDNODE
@NODE ZOOM "ARexx function ZOOM"
@TOC GestionĀfenĻtres

    @{B}ZOOM(ratio)@{UB}

    This command can modify the scale of the display. The ratio can be
    between 25 (scale is then equal to 25%) and 1000 (maximum zoom).
    If the argument is outside these values, the function has no effect.

    The returned value is the scale that was used before the function was
    executed.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "CommandesĀclavier" "Use of the keyboard"
@TOC "MAIN"

    HELP

    Launches the program AmigaGuide, this one loads the help file
    AmiCAD.guide.
    This guide must be in the directory where the AmiCAD programis located,
    or at the place specified by the tooltype @{"HELPFILE" LINK HELPFILE}.

    @{b}Edit commands@{ub}

    DEL:	Erasure of the selected objects

    @{b}CURSOR keys@{ub}

    ARROW (LEFT/RIGHT/UP/DOWN):
    The selected elements are moved, pixel by pixel or 10 pixels if the
    SHIFT key is also pressed.

    ALT ARROW:
    Edit the rays of the selected arc, pixel by pixel or 10 pixels if the
    SHIFT key is also pressed.

    CONTROL ARROW:
    Edit the angles of the selected arc, degree by degree or by variation
    of 10 degrees if the SHIFT key is also pressed.

    CTRL:
    Allows deselection of elements if used at the same time as the left
    button of the mouse during the selection.

    TAB:	copy (clone) selected elements

    ALT HELP:	brief display of the role of keys ALT with the function keys.
    ALT F1/F10: programming of macro-command, then replaying.
    SHIFT ALT F1/F10: reprogramming of the macro-commands.

    @{b}Utilisation of the FUNCTION keys@{ub}

    F3	     :	open a new window, choosing a file to load
    F4	     :	open a new window
    F9	     :	move the screen behind
    F10      :	move the window behind
@ENDNODE
@NODE "TouchesĀfonction" "Utilisation des touches de fonction"
@TOC Macros

    The ten function keys can be associated with sequences of commands
    including calls to functions which you will have defined.
    These programmed sequences are saved in the file "s:AmiCAD.keys",
    using the menu @{"Preferences/Keys/Save file" LINK Keys}.
    These will then be reloaded during each execution of the program.

    The call of a combination is done while pressing on ALT and the key of
    the desired function.  The redefinition of this key can be done while
    pressing on keys SHIFT and ALT before pressing on the function key to
    redefine.

  Example:
      - the programmed sequence @{"SETGRID" LINK SETGRID}(5) is on the key F1,
    a) press ALT, SHIFT and finally F1,
    b) a requester is opened, showing the macro there:
	SETGRID(5)
    c) confirm, the definition is saved in memory,
    d) press now the keys ALT and F1, the macro is carried out.

    To redefine it later on, start again at a).
@ENDNODE
@NODE GTLAYOUT gtlayout.library
@TOC MAIN

    The author of the gtlayout.library is Olaf `Olsen' Barthel.
    This library is available in the public domain, (Aminet dev/gui, sources included).
@ENDNODE
@NODE "AideĀenĀligne" "Online Help"
@TOC "MAIN"

    An online help can be obtained constantly, using the AmiCAD.guide file.
    This file must be located in the same directory as the program or at a
    place and a name specified in the tooltype @{"HELPFILE" LINK HELPFILE }
    of the AmiCAD program icon, (this information is taken into account
    during the execution of the program).

    To launch the assistance you can press on the HELP key, immediately or
    during the selection of a menu, which enables you to have direct
    assistance concerning this menu.  You can also use the menu
    @{"Project/Help" LINK "Help?"} and give the name of a node, (node), of the help
    file.  You can thus find help very quickly for any function, by giving
    it's name.

    Note that you can also get help for an error caused by a function.
    Press on the HELP key when the requester announcing the error is
    displayed.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "MacrosĀutiles" "Useful macros"
@TOC Macros

    The following definitions can be integrated into the AmiCAD.keys file,
    either using a text editor, or by defining them under AmiCAD (see
    function @{"MAP" LINK MAP}) then by choosing the menu @{"Preferences/Keys/Save file" LINK Keys}.

    Macro to allow choosing a component by typing only the first letters of
    it's name (even only the first):
  IF((PP=ASK('Component?'))<>'', GETPART(PP):MENU('Place'), 0)

    Macro to allow a call to a function associated with another macro, for
    all the selected objects, (here it is MACRO(5) which is called, that is
    to say the macro defined on key F5):
  O=FIRSTSEL:WHILE(O, MACRO(5):O=NEXTSEL(O))

    Selection of all the elements on the document:
  MARKZONE(0,0,WWIDTH(-1)-1,WHEIGHT(-1)-1)

    Loading of a library of components by requester, without using the gtlayout
    requester:
  LOADLIB(ASK("Library to load?"))
    or better:
  IF((LIB=ASK("Library to load?"))<>"", LOADLIB(LIB), 0)

    Addition of the sign "ohm" to the value of a resistance, (the VALUE of
    resistance in question must only be selected):
  SETTEXT(FIRSTSEL, READTEXT(FIRSTSEL) CHR(139))

    Loading of a clip, move this clip under the cursor:
  LOADCLIP(1, "Additionneur"):MENU("Copy")

    To bind a text to a component, (as a value or a reference):
  LINKVAL(FIRSTSEL, PICKOBJ("Click on the value of this component"))
  LINKREF(FIRSTSEL, PICKOBJ("Click on the reference of this component"))
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Bugs" "BUG(s) ?   (mais oui !  s¹rement... (malheureusement !) )"

    This program required much work by me so I would kindly request you to
    be lenient for the always possible errors occurring during it's use.
    I would be grateful to you for agreeing to inform @{"me" LINK Auteur} if you note
    one or more anomalies.

    The use of the program under a CyberGraphics screen can sometimes give
    odd results, (the function of COMPLEMENT drawing mode does not function
    or very badly, for area fills, whereas the same program functions
    perfectly under AGA modes).

    It can happen that a System Error occurs during the execution of an
    ARexx script, if a command causes an error.  This problem is normally
    avoided by following the structure given in the example script New.AmiCAD
    for ARexx scripts.

    The AmiCAD screen is a public screen, thus you can open one, (or even
    several), other application on it's screen.  However, always close these
    other windows BEFORE leaving AmiCAD, if not there can be some problems...
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Historique" "History"

@{b}Version 2.14@{ub}	@{i}March 26 2004@{ui}
    Modification of the @{"MARK" LINK MARK} macro.

@{b}Version 2.13@{ub}	@{i}January 23 2004@{ui}
    Help key handled when requesters are opened.

@{b}Version 2.12@{ub}	@{i}December 12 2003@{ui}
    A document can now include several pages.
    Modification of the @{b}TOOLBAR@{ub} macro.
    Toolbars have not to be closed when changing screen mode.
    New macros @{"NEWPAGE" LINK NEWPAGE}, @{"SETPAGE" LINK SETPAGE} and @{"PAGES" LINK PAGES}.
    Menus "Preferences/Objects scale" removed (Use the macro SETSCALE
    in place, if needed).

@{b}Version 2.11@{ub}	@{i}October 5 2003@{ui}
    Printer handler modified (if printer.device already opened).

@{b}Version 2.10@{ub}	@{i}October 21 2002@{ui}
    New "Full page" button on printing requester.

@{b}Version 2.09d@{ub}	 @{i}May 23 2002@{ui}
    New @{"SETPULL" LINK SETPULL} macro.

@{b}Version 2.09c@{ub}	 @{i}January 13 2002@{ui}
    Recompiled using the NDK_3.9 kit.
    New @{"CADPATH" LINK CADPATH} macro.

@{b}Version 2.09b@{ub}	 @{i}September 29 2001@{ui}
    Placement of the toolbar to front after printing.
    Toolbar handler modified (command is sent when the mouse button is
    released). You can edit a command clicking with the two buttons on
    an icon.
    No activation of the control printing window (could lead to a non
    volontary cancel of the printing if using the keyboard at this
    moment).

@{b}Version 2.09@{ub}	 @{i}September 9 2001@{ui}
    Bug correction of the @{"LOADCLIP" LINK LOADCLIP} function (caused a lock on
    the specified clip), better @{"SAVECLIP" LINK SAVECLIP} handling (uses the
    @{"CLIPS" LINK CLIPS} tooltypes or the @{"CLIPPATH" LINK CLIPPATH} function path).
    New attribute for components (PCB mask).
    New ARexx macros: @{"GETMASK" LINK GETMASK}, @{"SETMASK" LINK SETMASK}, @{"MASKPATH" LINK MASKPATH}, @{"VISIBLE" LINK VISIBLE}
    New tooltype: @{"MASKS" LINK MASKS}.
    Modification of the Preferences menu (placed before the Scripts and Macros menus).
    Adaptation of AmiCAD2META to the new objects (PCB masks).
    Correction and adaptation of this guide (Startup preferences still to do).
    Modification of the search macros (FINDOBJ, FINDREF, FINDVAL, FINDLAB,
    FINDLINE, FINDPART) to handle only selected objects when the
    object number is in negative form.
    New components added in libraries (input/output connectors, circuits with
    n pins) for creating netlists for AmiPCB with "exotic" components.
    New @{"Edition/Select net" LINK "SelectĀnet"} menu.

@{b}Version 2.08@{ub}	 @{i}March 25, 2001@{ui}
    New Label object (connected to wires).
    New functions @{"GETLABEL" LINK GETLABEL}, @{"LINKLAB" LINK LINKLAB}, @{"SETLABEL" LINK SETLABEL}, @{"FINDLAB" LINK FINDLAB}, @{"GETNET" LINK GETNET}.
    Functions @{"SETREF" LINK SETREF}, @{"SETVAL" LINK SETVAL} modified (returned values).
    New functions @{"ARRAYDIM" LINK ARRAYDIM}, @{"DIMARRAY" LINK DIMARRAY}, @{"DELARRAY" LINK DELARRAY}, @{"GETARRAY" LINK GETARRAY} and @{"SETARRAY" LINK SETARRAY} (to handle
    data arrays).
    Mousemove events handler modified (uses now the interval defined
    in the Preferences of the system for a double click before moving
    anything, to avoid troubles while clicking fastly on objects).

@{b}Version 2.07a@{ub}	  @{i}January 1, 2001@{ui}
    Bug correction modulo operator (%)

@{b}Version 2.07@{ub}	 @{i}Novembre 12, 2000@{ui}
  New function @{"LANGUAGE" LINK LANGUAGE} (to localize scripts).
  Bug correction loading a clip (many hits Enforcer if component not found).
  Modification of functions @{"HSCALE" LINK HSCALE} and @{"VSCALE" LINK VSCALE} to get the
  current scales.
  Checking boxes (clicks) more accurate.
  Some enhancements to this guide (history, some new functions added...)
  If the program was launched from shell with an argument, if this
  argument was a file that was not found, the program didn't display
  an error message: bug corrected.
  New swedish catalog by Henrik Isaksson: henisak@algonet.se
  Bug correction saving function keys (a _ char was joined to the string
  defining the key name).

@{b}Version 2.06@{ub}	 @{i}Novembre 1, 2000@{ui}
  Bug correction to the key handler. Gtlayout.library version number changed (45).
  New button to get a functions list requester on macro-commands requester.
  New "Application" button on edition requesters to extend or not the
  modification on other objects.
  New finnish catalog by Joni Halme: halmej@saunalahti.fi

@{b}Version 2.05@{ub}	 @{i}Avril 14, 2000@{ui}
  Bug correction when pulling lines (a wire was sometimes moved twice).
  Bug correction for printing (could lead to a crash if the last line was
  filled)
  Printing by bands (request less chip memory, can print larger
  documents, even with a high resolution, like when using laser printer).
  Multitask (each window is handled by a separate process),
  modification of the ARexx interface : some functions has been
  removed (@{"NEW" LINK NEW}, @{"SELFILE" LINK SELFILE}, @{"LOADKEYS" LINK LOADKEYS}, @{"LOADPREF" LINK LOADPREF},
  @{"MACRO" LINK MACRO}, @{"SAVEKEYS" LINK SAVEKEYS} @{"SAVEPREF" LINK SAVEPREF}, @{"SELSHEET" LINK SELSHEET}, @{"NBSHEET" LINK NBSHEET}),
  some functions have been added: (@{"NEWSHEET" LINK NEWSHEET}, @{"NBSHEETS" LINK NBSHEETS}, @{"REXXPORT" LINK REXXPORT})
  or modified (@{"CLOSE" LINK CLOSE}, @{"MODIF" LINK MODIF}, @{"LOCK" LINK LOCK}, @{"UNLOCK" LINK UNLOCK}, @{"SAVEALL" LINK SAVEALL}, @{"OBJECTS" LINK OBJECTS}, @{"FONTNAME" LINK FONTNAME},
  @{"FONTSIZE" LINK FONTSIZE}, @{"WWIDTH" LINK WWIDTH}, @{"WHEIGHT" LINK WHEIGHT}, @{"GETZONE" LINK GETZONE}, @{"REQSHEET" LINK REQSHEET}, @{"WTOFRONT" LINK WTOFRONT}, @{"WTOBACK" LINK WTOBACK}).
  Some options availables with Shell has been suppressed :
  MACRO, @{"SHEET_WIDTH" LINK SHEET_WIDTH}, @{"SHEET_HEIGHT" LINK SHEET_HEIGHT}, some tooltypes has also been
  removed : @{"WINDOW" LINK OUTILĀWINDOW}, @{"MACRO" LINK _MACROS}, @{"GRIDSIZE" LINK GRIDSIZE}.  These parameters can be
  fixed using the new preferences menu.

@{B}Version 2.04@{UB}	 @{I}(November 28, 1999)@{UI}
  Bug correction of value/reference placement to the left of a component.
  Modification of the arcs handler (slower but cleaner).
  Lines width requester modified (was buggy if a special line was edited)
  Extension is now possible for boxes, arcs, triangles, ellipses.
  Bug correction of AmiCAD2META (caused a crash of the Amiga when
  being runned in previous version), thanks to Arno Richter).
  New component "Bornier" in Symboles_ķlectriques library.
  New german catalogs for symbol libraries AmiCAD, "divers" and "logiques"
  (Thanks to Gu0cky). New english catalog for "logiques" symbols (myself).
  File requester handler enhanced (AmiCAD windows refresh is possible
  while a requester is opened).
  Modication of function keys handler: we can now program these
  keys using any qualifier (ALT, SHIFT and (or) CTRL) or not.
  A new menu and requester has been added to program these keys.
  ARexx @{"MACRO" LINK MACRO} macro suppressed.
  Nouvelle @{"REQLIST" LINK REQLIST} function.

@{B}Version 2.03 @{UB}	 @{I}(September 26, 1999)@{UI}
  New requesters for editing objects.
  Bug correction of @{"MAP" LINK MAP} function, new MapKey script.

@{B}Version 2.02@{UB}	 @{I}(August/September 1999)@{UI}
  Replacement of the bgui.library by the gtlayout.library (code is
    now shortest and faster).

@{B}Version 2.01@{UB}	 @{I}(Mai 1999)@{UI}
  Som bugs correction of display when using "Auto-scroll" mode.
  Modification of the function @{"COORDS" LINK COORDS} to get data from
    angles and ellipses (radius, angles).
  New toolbar handler (@{"TOOLBAR" LINK TOOLBAR}).
  Modification of the @{"MENU" LINK MENU} function for using menu headers
    given in english, whith any locale being used.
  Modification of functions @{"DELETE" LINK DELETE} and @{"SAVEIFF" LINK SAVEIFF}.
  New function @{"LIBRARY" LINK LIBRARY}.
  New @{"Edition/Scale" LINK Scale} menu to change the scale of objects.

@{B}Version 2.00@{UB}	 @{I}(March 1999)@{UI}
  New functions @{"CURSMODE" LINK CURSMODE}, @{"SETORTHO" LINK SETORTHO}, @{"SNAPGRID" LINK SNAPGRID}, @{"GETLINE" LINK GETLINE}, @{"GETZONE" LINK GETZONE}.
  Modification of the objects scale handler (now given in percentage:
    100 gives a normal scale).
  New files format (use the ARexx script ImportFile_1.0 to load your old
  files).
  New zoom (from 25 to 1000%, see also ARexx function @{"ZOOM" LINK ZOOM}).
  Bug correction of loosed allocated memory when loading a clip.
  Bug correction of functions @{"SELSHEET" LINK SELSHEET} and @{"SELFILE" LINK SELFILE} that caused
    the selected windows to be locked.
  Middle mouse button now used to select the current document.
  Modification of function @{"REQFILE" LINK REQFILE}.

@{B}Version 1.6@{UB}	@{I}(not distributed)@{UI}
  Type of connector now displayed (Input or Output) when editing.
  ENTER key used to edit the first selected object, or to place an objet.
  Modification of functions COL, LINE, HEIGHT and WIDTH to know the
    placement and dimensions of the current selected objects.
  Bug correction of clips rotation display.
  Modification of connectors handler (alternate symbol, symmetry).
  Modification of the @{"UNLINK" LINK UNLINK} function (unlinking value or reference
    only is now possible).
  Bug correction for printing square junctions (version 1.5 crashed...)
  Bug correction for handling boxes symmetry.
  Bug correction when copying with no current selection (the current clipboard was flushed).
  New @{"GETPOINT" LINK GETPOINT}, @{"ASKTEXT" LINK ASKTEXT} and @{"ASKNUM" LINK ASKNUM} functions.
  Functions ASK and GETPART suppressed (replaced by @{"ASKTEXT" LINK ASKTEXT} and @{"PUTPART" LINK PUTPART}).

@{B}Version 1.5@{UB}	@{I}November 2, 1998@{UI}
  New menus defined by the user.
  Adaptation of the utility @{"AmiCAD2META" LINK AmiCAD2META} to the format of libraries,
  bug reported by Henk Jonas.
  New requester to permit to stop printing before it's finished.
  Saving faster (thanks to Sķbastien VEYRIN-FORRER).
  Saving the menu "Preferences/Full name" state now works (report from David Beryl).
  Correction bug function @{"PENWIDTH" LINK PENWIDTH}.
  New square junctions (using the menu "Drawing/Alternate symbol").
  Problem opening screen requester in PAL mode solved... (?)

@{b}Version 1.4@{ub}
  New ARexx functions @{"GETDEVS" LINK GETDEVS}, @{"GROUP" LINK GROUP}, @{"UNGROUP" LINK UNGROUP}.

@{b}Version 1.3@{ub} June 1, 1998
  Correction of the buggy function "To restore it" (finally...?)
  Corrections bugs processing boxes (impression and clips)...
  Correction bug function @{"SETPINS" LINK SETPINS}. Addition function @{"BOX" LINK BOX}.
  Modification of functions @{"WRITE" LINK WRITE}, @{"INPUT" LINK INPUT} and @{"OUTPUT" LINKOUTPUT}.

@{b}Version 1.2@{ub} April 12, 1998
  Corrections bugs:  function DATES, use sometimes failing functions
  user (DEF), functions SETDEV, SETGRID, REMLIB...
  Addition functions @{"SAVEALL" LINK SAVEALL} and @{"GETCOLOR" LINK GETCOLOR}.
  Improvement of the management of small Symmetry.  Addition of the
  processing of the operations of rotation, symmetry, enlarging and
  reduction on the clip in progress.
  Passage of the screen from 8 to 16 colours:  the elements are now
  drawn different colours, according to their type.
  Addition of the right-angled object (not of dotted lines for the
  moment).
  Addition of a menu in the preferences to keep or not the complete
  name of the file in the bar of title.  Modification of the
  indications carried in the bar of title (suggestion of Sebastien
  VEYRIN-FORRER).
  Improvement of script Roasts (creation of a grid in the rectangle
  defined by the user).
  Addition of the Italian catalogue (by Massimo Basso), new version
  of the Spanish catalogue (Benjamin Morente).
  Localisation of the symbols library.

@{b}Version 1.1@{ub} March 8, 1998
  Replacement of the file of Configuration.AmiCAD configuration by the
  file AmiCAD.prefs (more need to use ConfigFile.library, however the
  new files of configuration are not compatible with the old ones).
  Improvement of the script of installation.
  Writing of the German catalogue (by Henk Joans).
  Modification opening screen (screen of size equal to that of Workbench
  by defect).
  Correction of some small bugs (width of the buttons in the requests,
  width of the iconified windows, management macro ARexx SYMMETRY) as
  well as few others more significant (macro @{"LOADCLIP" LINK LOADCLIP}).
  Addition tooltypes @{"SHEET_WIDTH" LINK SHEET_WIDTH} and @{"SHEET_HEIGHT" LINK SHEET_HEIGHT}.
  Some optimizations of the code (shorter program).
  Addition edition width milks component, texts, ellipses, arcs, etc.
  Modification management of the arrows cursor for displacement of the
  objects and edition arcs and ellipses.
  Modification of the management of the groups.
  Addition of the function ARexx @{"SETPINS" LINK SETPINS}.
  Suppression of the use of ConfigFile.library, replaced by internal,
  shorter routines.
  Correction bug colours screen AGA.
  Suppression of the ' requesters ', replaced by windows...

@{b}Version 1.00@{ub}  18 janvier 1998
  First version, written for system 3.0. 1st diffusion on Aminet.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "AidezMoi" "Help-me!!"

    This program can be very enhanced. But I have not got all the docs that
    I need and not much time. So, if you can send me some docs or do a part
    of the translation of this guide, @{"mail me!" LINK Auteur}.

    For the moment I'm looking for documentation on the following items:
    - description of the EPSF format (for saving under this format, to load
      the sheets with a program like ProPage or another)...
    - routines of "clipping", to draw an object even if it's not completely
      in the window, (lines, but also circles, arcs, filled areas...)
    - description of the "printer.device", (how to know the number of
      pixels that can be set by the current printer on a line, using the
      Amiga preferences).
    - how to use vector fonts, (CompuGraphics or Adobe...), like ProPage or
      WordWorth.
    - etc...

  Thanks for your suggestions and collaboration.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Amķliorations" "Possible future enhancements"

    The following improvements will be made if the need is felt and if I have
    time to do them, (and also if I'm brave enough!)
    - choice of icon created by the program at the time of a save,
    - improvement of error message text, often vague,
    - improvement of function MAP (visualization and choice of macros already
      defined),
    - marking of a site in the diagram to find quickly, (practical in a
      large diagram),
    - requester to allow the choice of an object when there has to be a
      superposition,
    - writing an internal zoom function, (I use the freeware Lupe of
      Frank Toepper),
    - writing a library editor,
    - and more still... (see @{"HELP!" Link AidezMoi})

  If you wish to translate this documentation or well the file
    catalogues, thank you me to communicate them so that they are
    distributed with the program.
@ENDNODE
